# Cyrius Field Notes — Compiler Internal Gotchas
# Non-obvious traps an agent will hit when working on cyrius's
# compiler internals: regalloc, layout, alignment, IR ordering,
# heap caps, fn-table conventions, codegen-vs-IR divergence.
#
# Earn their slot when an agent is debugging a cyrius
# regression that doesn't fit a clean pattern. The shape is
# always "this surprised future-me; here's the diagnosis +
# fix + how to recognize it again."
#
# For process methodology see methodology.cyml.
# For design patterns see patterns.cyml.
# For full backstory + chronological context see retros/.
#
# 48 entries (6.2.0 added, Phase-0 growable pressure tables: the GROW / REHASH /
# RELOCATION paths (fn-table 16-table realloc + fn_name_hash rehash; codebuf
# off-heap relocate) are SELF-HOST-INVISIBLE — cycc's 6486 fns / ~1 MB codebuf
# never reach the 8192 / 3 MB caps, so self-host + check.sh never exercise them;
# only a forced-grow test (shrink _fnt_cap/_codebuf_cap to 64/8192, self-compile,
# cmp vs the no-grow reference) catches relocation/rehash bugs. Also: the 8192
# fn-cap was a magic number scattered across 6 subsystems + colliding TEXTUALLY
# with 5 unrelated 8192-capped tables — the migration needed surgical per-context
# swaps (& 8191 → mask, probe/clear bounds → cap, live[1024] DCE bitmap → [4096]),
# never a global replace. See the two phase0_growable_* entries.)
# 44 entries (6.1.40 added, CVE-24: the four per-fn local tables
# (fn_local_names/depths/types/slice) are indexed by SFLC, which counts stack-frame
# SLOTS not vars — a `stack var buf[N]` registers N/8 fillers — so frames >~2 KB
# silently overran the old 256/576-entry tables; relocated all four to the heap top
# (0x5D9D000/0x5DBD000/0x5DDD000/0x5DFD000) at 16384 slots each + a loud SFLC cap.
# Plus the local-vs-global array convention: local `var a[N]` = N BYTES rounded to
# 8; global = N i64 SLOTS — the footgun behind the daimon report.)
# 43 entries (6.1.18 added: adding a PUBLIC stdlib fn (a top-level `module::fn` in
# lib/) makes check.sh's api-surface gate fail cryptically — `case-FAIL: test3
# addition count not reported as 1` — because docs/api-surface.snapshot is now
# stale; regenerate it: rebuild build/cyrius_api_surface from source then
# `build/cyrius_api_surface --update`. Underscore-private fns + src/backend
# internals are NOT tracked, so only intended public-surface adds show. Also: a
# new lib/<x>_win.cyr should be SELF-CONTAINED (own widen/narrow) — coupling it to
# _args_w2u8/_w_append_cstr forces every Windows consumer of the parent module to
# include args.cyr/process.cyr, FATAL under --strict.)
# 42 entries (6.1.17 added: a NEW PE syscall-reroute emitter `E*_PE` must get an
# aarch64 `return 0` stub in backend/aarch64/emit.cyr — parse_expr.cyr references
# it unconditionally inside the statically-dead `_TARGET_PE==1` block, and a
# missing stub fires "undefined function" which is FATAL under `--strict` on
# aarch64 (cx tolerates the whole cohort un-stubbed, aarch64 does NOT). The build
# passes WITHOUT the stub if you forget `--strict` — the warning is the only tell.)
# 41 entries (6.1.12 added: a large fn-local `var[]` lands in `.bss` static, NOT
# the stack — and a `var[]` in a statically-dead region after a `#ifdef`-gated
# return STILL reserves its `.bss`; diagnose via `objdump -h` section deltas, not
# `sub rsp` scanning. The agnos getenv #PF was `.bss`-image/loader-mapping, not
# stack overflow as the issue assumed.)
# 40 entries (.88-.90 added: x86-Mach-O can't compile byte-array literals — a
# parser miscompile INVISIBLE to self-host since cycc uses no byte arrays (verify
# pre-existing by stashing to the released tag's source on the target); the
# byte-array peephole must hoist &var via the obj-aware _EVRCX, NOT absolute-only
# EVADDR_X1, or obj/PIE byte arrays regress; _emit_fmt must test Mach-O before PE
# to match the old EMITELF ladder for the unguarded CYRIUS_MACHO+CYRIUS_TARGET_WIN
# combo. Plus the zsh-no-word-split test-harness trap.)
# 37 entries (.87 added: getenv on agnos walks the exec-stack envp from
# _agnos_init_rsp (no /proc); the agnos kernel is LOCALLY TESTABLE — rebuild
# with agnos/scripts/build.sh + boot under QEMU via agnsh-smoke.sh/exec-smoke.sh
# and run a ring-3 cyrius binary. Don't claim "no agnos to test on".)
# 36 entries (.86 added: callptr callee-spill frame slot can ALIAS a &-taken
# local — v6.0.70 spilled the indirect-call target to a GFLC frame slot; a COM
# out-param `&local` could land on the same slot → frame/regalloc corruption →
# AV (DXGI GetDesc1 on cass). Fix: PE callptr callee on the STACK + `call rax`,
# no frame slot. Found with cdb on cass (C:\dbg\cdb.exe).
# 35 entries (.85 added: Windows install pillar — no /proc env on Windows (read
# via GetEnvironmentVariableA PE reroute 0xF015); wrapper compile()/run_binary
# are POSIX fork/execve, Windows needs cmd.exe-redirect spawn via CreateProcessW
# (cmd /s /c strips only the outer quote pair); .ps1 must be ASCII (PS 5.1
# mis-decodes UTF-8 em-dashes); the macho-arm/x86 dual-number trap applies to PE
# reroute numbers too. cyrius build now works on Windows.
# 34 entries (.84 added: macOS owns the thread-pointer register — Darwin
# saves/restores TPIDR_EL0 (arm64) / %fs (x86) as thread state and overwrites
# any userspace install on the FIRST preemption, so cyrius can't durably own it
# for thread-local storage (sigil crypto-scratch crash); use a process-global
# on macOS. + socketpair dual-number: arm-macho=199 (aarch64-Linux enum),
# x86-macho=53 — and 53 is fchmodat on the arm enum, so don't reuse it.
# 33 entries (.70 added: callptr/IR_CALL_INDIRECT — compiler-emitted indirect
# calls; the callee-survival crux (frame-slot spill, NOT pop-after-ECALLPOPS
# which the Win64 shadow buries); aarch64 uses x6; top-level/cx = loud error;
# open real-Win64-COM-callee corruption → .71.
# 32 entries (.69 added: PE multi-DLL imports — generalize the single-kernel32
# import descriptor to N DLLs (shell32/dxgi); the flat ftype=4 fixup forces an
# imp_idx→physical-slot remap; design byte-identical at one DLL; x86-only PE
# emit fns need aarch64 no-op stubs (FATAL under --strict).
# .68 added: aarch64-Linux ESYSXLAT gaps — stat/rename/symlink
# literals hit the wrong aarch64 syscall (§D1 deps + build + pulsar); the
# native entry file diverged from the cross (missing auto-call-main); and the
# CI gate tested the cross binary not the shipped native one (placebo).
# .67 added: param_load(reg,idx) asm pseudo + the bootstrap-coupling
# lesson — migrating bootstrap-critical libs to a new compiler feature.
# .66 added: cyrius test on Apple Silicon — qemu mis-route (127)
# + unsigned AMFI SIGKILL (137); exec native + _macho_codesign in run_binary.
# .65 added: portable sleep — no raw nanosleep(35) off Linux;
# poll-as-sleep + Windows Sleep reroute; macho 35 collides with unlinkat.
# .64 added: aarch64 atomic-on-global needs 8-aligned
# var base; aarch64 atomic_cas is not a full barrier — fence the lock.
# .63 added: macho syscall dual-definition 61-vs-217;
# Mach-O output-basename breaks reproducible cmp).

[[entries]]
name = "element_typed_array_slot_spelling_v621"
description = "Bare `var a[N]` is byte-sized in a fn / slot-sized at top level — an accidental divergence that silently corrupts any address-taken local written with the `store64(&a + i*8)` slot idiom (the daimon route-404 class). v6.2.1 adds `var a: T[N]` (N elements of T) as the unambiguous slot/typed spelling; the audit found the class live in cycc itself (PARSE_SWITCH/PARSE_MATCH jump tables) + stdlib + folded libs."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["layout", "var-array", "byte-vs-slot", "0x12A000", "daimon", "v6.2.1"]
content = """
**The trap**: the SAME syntax `var a[N]` reserves different sizes by
scope. In a function (`PARSE_ARRAY`, parse_decl.cyr) it's `(N+7)&~7`
**bytes**; at top level (`PARSE_GVAR_ARR`) it's `N*8` (N i64 **slots**).
Both register into the one var-size table at `0x12A000`. A
function-local slot array written with `store64(&a + i*8, …)` therefore
runs off its byte-sized backing — `var parts[4]` is 8 bytes (1 slot),
so `store64(&parts + 24, …)` corrupts the next static object. Layout-
sensitive, so it stays dormant until an unrelated change shifts the
layout (daimon: deleting dead code moved `parts` 24 B before sandhi's
`" "` literal → every HTTP route 404'd).

**The fix (v6.2.1)**: `var a: T[N]` = N elements of T, sized
`N*sizeof(T)` identically in BOTH scopes. `i64[N]` = N slots (the slot
spelling), `u8[N]` = N bytes, widths i8..i64/u8..u64/u128. Pure
**frontend** change — the element width threads through `scalar_type`
(in-fn, `PARSE_ARRAY(S,noff,ew)`) / `ann_scalar` (top-level,
`PARSE_GVAR_ARR(S,noff,sti,ew)`) into the `0x12A000` byte size, and
every backend (x86/aarch64/macho/pe/cx) inherits it by SUMMING that
table — no backend edits. Bare `var a[N]` keeps its legacy per-scope
meaning (best reserved for byte buffers).

**Two-step bootstrap REQUIRED when migrating cycc's OWN arrays**:
because the OLD build/cycc byte-sizes the new `i64[N]` annotation,
`build/cycc → stage_a` gives stage_a byte-sized internal tables;
`stage_a → stage_b` (stage_a has the feature) gives slot-sized tables.
So `stage_a != stage_b`; the fixpoint is `stage_b == stage_c`. cycc's
own source had no >32-arm switch/match, so the under-sized `ends[256]`
(32 slots) self-hosted by luck for years — the classic latent-until-
layout-shift signature.

**Audit lesson**: run the audit against the lib SOURCE repos, not the
vendored fold — the fold-copy scan missed sigil `snp_report_verify`'s
`parsed[4]` that the source check caught (same `memset(&x,0,32)`-on-an-
8-byte-buffer bug as its sibling `inters[4]`). The ecosystem libs
(sigil/sakshi/agnosys) are the language's own stdlibs: patch each
lib's source, hold for release, then re-fold — never hand-edit the
`# Do not edit` vendored copy.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "large_fn_local_var_array_is_bss_not_stack"
description = "A large function-local `var buf[N]` in cycc is allocated in `.bss` static storage, NOT the stack frame — and a `var[]` sitting in a statically-dead region (e.g. after a `#ifdef`-gated early `return`) STILL reserves its `.bss` even on the path that never reaches it. Diagnose via section deltas, not `sub rsp` scanning."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["layout", "bss", "var-array", "agnos", "stack", "v6.1.12"]
content = """
**The trap**: `lib/io.cyr` `getenv()` had an 8 KB `var buf[8192]`
*after* a `#ifdef CYRIUS_TARGET_AGNOS` early `return`. The agnos
build never touches `buf`, but the agnoshi consumer #PF'd and the
filed issue blamed an "8 KB stack frame reserved past the early
return." Plausible — but WRONG about the mechanism.

**What actually happens**: in cycc a function-local `var[]` of
this size is emitted into **`.bss`** (static storage), not as a
stack-frame allocation. Verified on the real `--agnos` build by
diffing section sizes before/after guarding the buffer behind
`#ifndef CYRIUS_TARGET_AGNOS`:

  .bss   0x2f18 -> 0xf08   (-8208 B = buf + align)
  .text  -928 B            (the now-dead environ reader)
  max stack frame: unchanged at 0xd0 — no `sub rsp, 0x2000`
  ever existed.

So scanning the disassembly for a big `sub rsp` finds nothing and
can make you think "the buffer isn't there" — it IS, just in
`.bss`. Always check `llvm-objdump -h` section deltas, not just
prologue `sub rsp`, when chasing a "phantom buffer" on a
constrained target.

**Why it still faulted on agnos** (mechanism the issue got wrong):
an oversized `.bss` grows the PT_LOAD memsz the loader must
zero-map; the agnos #PF is `.bss`-image / loader-mapping related,
NOT init-stack overflow. A "widen the ring-3 init stack" fix
aims a layer off.

**The fix**: guard the whole reader (buffer + parse loop) behind
`#ifndef CYRIUS_TARGET_AGNOS` so the dead region contributes
nothing to the agnos image. The broader compiler-side want —
elide storage for a `var[]` that's provably never live on the
taken path — stays a (low-priority) follow-on; the preprocessor
guard fully resolves the case. Related: the v6.0.79 `cyml.cyr`
oversized-`var[]`-on-constrained-target overflow.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "slice_fn_local_layout_flip"
description = "Pre-§8 16-byte fn-local slices put the canonical slot at the higher stack address; `&slice + 8` overflowed past the local frame into saved-rbp territory. §8 layout-flip (v5.8.16) allocates the high-half slot FIRST (higher address) and the canonical slot SECOND (lower address)."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["slices", "layout", "stack", "v5.8.16"]
content = """
**The trap**: pre-v5.8.16, `var s: [u8] = 0;` allocated a
single canonical slot (the named slot, where `&s` resolves)
and a sentinel-cleared high-half slot. The canonical slot was
the LOWER-numbered slot (higher stack address per cyrius's
slot-N-at-rbp-(N+1)*8 convention). `slice_set(&s, ptr, len)`
did `store64(s+8, len)`, which on the stack means
`store64(rbp - canon_disp + 8, len)` — overflowing past the
local frame into saved-rbp territory.

This corrupted the caller's saved rbp. Worked anyway:

  1. Round-tripped within the fn — slice_set wrote and slice_len
     read the same (corrupted) location.
  2. `slices_typing.tcyr`'s `return slice_len(&x);` form passed
     because main's rbp = 0 from the C runtime — the read
     returned 0 by coincidence.
  3. §7 indexing tests passed because each test exited via
     `syscall(60, ...)` before any code referenced the corrupted
     rbp.

**Surfaced when**: §8 introduced `s.len` reads via &s+8
(memory I/O through the canonical-slot address) — same
arithmetic as slice_set, but the test reading expected a
deterministic value, not "whatever happened to be at saved rbp."

**Fix**: for `scalar_type==16`, allocate the HIGH-HALF slot
FIRST (slot li, higher address) and the CANONICAL slot SECOND
(slot li+1, lower address). The name + meta live on slot li+1
so FINDLOCAL returns it; EFLADDR(li+1) yields the lower
address; EFLADDR(li+1) + 8 lands on slot li (higher address) —
matching the slice convention's "second 8 bytes."

Init both halves: zero the canonical slot via EFLSTORE(li+1)
and zero the high half via address-based memory store
(EFLADDR_X1 + EADDIMM_X1(8) + ESTOC). Address-based init for
the high half is required because the regalloc post-body
peephole would patch EFLSTORE(li) to `mov rbx, rax` (writing
to a register, not the stack slot). See `slice_high_half_regalloc_pin`.

**Recognize again**: any "fn-local 16-byte type silently fails"
shape. If two adjacent `var x: u128` or `var s: [T]` interact
weirdly, check the layout-flip is still in place.

Full backstory: v5_8.cyml's `slice_fn_local_layout_flip_v5816`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "slice_high_half_regalloc_pin"
description = "Slice's high-half slot has no user-visible name; the regalloc post-body peephole would allocate a callee-saved register for it, leaving the actual stack slot uninitialized. §8 routes high-half I/O through address-based memory access to keep the slot in memory."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["slices", "regalloc", "v5.8.16"]
content = """
**The trap**: the regalloc post-body peephole (parse_fn.cyr
v5.6.20 picker) counts `mov [rbp+disp], rax` /
`mov rax, [rbp+disp]` patterns per slot to decide which user-
locals to pin to callee-saved registers (rbx, r12-r15). Time-
sliced sharing assumes every local interval starts with a STORE —
the register holds the right value from the start of each
interval, no LOAD-from-stack needed.

The slice's high-half slot has no user-visible name (sentinel-
cleared by the §8 layout-flip), so nothing else takes its
address via `&<ident>`. The picker's safety scan bars
`lea rax, [rbp+disp]` (treats `&local` as not-safe). Without
intervention, the high-half slot looks mov-only — picker
allocates rbx for it.

Then `var s: [T] = 0;`'s init `EFLSTORE(li, rax=0)` patches to
`mov rbx, rax` — writes 0 to rbx, leaves the stack slot
uninitialized. Subsequent slice_set memory-writes to the slot
are invisible to the register; `s.len` reads (which go through
the memory access path) see uninit stack data.

**Fix**: init the high half via address-based memory store
(EFLADDR_X1 + EADDIMM_X1(8) + ESTOC) rather than EFLSTORE.
The picker doesn't count memory-via-rcx writes, so the high
slot stays in memory. §8 dot-syntax (.len read/write) and
slice_len helper-fn calls all see the right value.

Same reasoning for §8 dot-syntax `s.len`: lower to address-
based load (EFLADDR_X1 + EADDIMM_X1(8) + ELODC), not direct
EFLLOAD against the slot. `s.ptr` could safely use EFLLOAD
(canonical slot is naturally barred from regalloc by slice_set
taking `&s`), but uses address-based for symmetry.

**Recognize again**: any "no-name auxiliary slot interacts
weirdly with regalloc" shape. The picker's safety scan only
bars slots with `&` taken via a NAMED ident; phantom slots
(high half of a 16-byte type, scratch slots) need explicit
exclusion.

Full backstory: v5_8.cyml's `slice_high_half_regalloc_pin_v5816`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "stale_fixed_cap_drift"
description = "Cap checks drift out of sync with the actual buffer size. The buffer gets expanded; the cap check / comment / docs DON'T. Bug sits latent until a downstream workload crosses the OLD threshold."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["caps", "drift", "diagnostics", "v3.4.20", "recurring"]
content = """
**The trap pattern**: cyrius uses fixed-size heap regions for
nearly every compiler data structure. Each region has an
explicit byte count (e.g., tok_names is 64 KB, preprocess_out
is 2 MB at v5.6.40). Most regions have a "capacity check"
somewhere in the code that silently caps or errors out when
the region fills.

Multiple times now, a capacity check has drifted out of sync
with the actual buffer size. The pattern:

1. Buffer gets expanded in one place (the actual allocation).
2. Cap check / comment / docs DON'T get updated in the other
   places.
3. Bug sits latent for N releases.
4. Some downstream workload crosses the OLD threshold.
5. Confusing error fires that doesn't point at the real
   buffer.
6. Delayed debugging session to figure out the stale cap is
   lying.

**Concrete instances**:

- v3.3.17 (Bug #33): LEXHEX read hex literals from the raw
  input buffer instead of the preprocessed buffer. Masked for
  years.
- v3.4.19: input_buf read loop capped at 131,072 bytes (the
  original 128 KB) silently — mabda's 141 KB bundle triggered
  the latent bug.
- v3.4.20 (lex.cyr:1077): preprocess_out cap checked
  `op > 524288` (512 KB), but the buffer was expanded to 1 MB
  in v3.4.5. Stale for FIVE releases.
- v3.4.20 (cyrius.toml roadmap): documented Input buffer as
  512 KB while actual code was 128 KB then 256 KB. Three
  different numbers across three files.

**The proactive sweep** (do at every minor closeout):

For each fixed-size buffer in cyrius, grep for EVERY
occurrence of the capacity constant (allocation AND cap
check) and confirm they agree. Also check comments, heap map,
docs, roadmap, and Open Limits table — all four need to match.

The Open Limits table in `docs/development/roadmap.md` is
worth special attention — it's the table downstream projects
read to decide how much headroom they have.

**The diagnostic discipline** (every fixed-size buffer):

Every fixed-size buffer should have an EXPLICIT overflow check
with a CLEAR error message pointing at the exact location to
fix:

```cyr
if (op > 1048576) {
    syscall(SYS_WRITE, 2,
        "error: expanded source exceeds 1MB (", 36);
    PRNUM(op);
    syscall(SYS_WRITE, 2,
        " bytes; raise preprocess_out cap in src/main.cyr)\\n", 50);
    syscall(SYS_EXIT, 1);
}
```

Silent truncation is never acceptable — it moves the symptom
arbitrarily far from the cause.

**Recognize again**: any error message reporting a numeric
threshold that doesn't match the comment / heap map / Open
Limits table.

Cross-ref: patterns.cyml's
`heap_cap_growth_compiler_grows_to_fit_language` (the dual —
when to RAISE caps vs when to discover stale caps).

Full backstory: retros/v3.cyml `stale_fixed_cap_pattern` +
`silent_stdin_truncation_saga`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "stdlib_alloc_grow_step_must_cover_request"
description = "Bump-allocator grow logic must cover the requested allocation, not a fixed delta. Fixed step `0x100000` regardless of requested size returned pointers past the brk/mmap for any alloc(>1MB)."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["alloc", "stdlib", "v5.6.x"]
content = """
**The trap**: bump allocator (`lib/alloc.cyr`) must grow its
backing region by AT LEAST the requested size, not a fixed
delta. Pre-fix, the grow logic was:

```cyr
if (alloc_used + n > brk_top) {
    sys_brk(brk_top + 0x100000);   # grow by 1 MB
    brk_top = brk_top + 0x100000;
}
return alloc_used; alloc_used = alloc_used + n;
```

For `alloc(1500000)` (1.5 MB request), the grow step adds 1 MB
but the requested size is 1.5 MB → returned pointer is past
the new brk_top. Subsequent stores write into unmapped memory
→ SIGSEGV.

**Fix**: grow by max(requested, fixed_step):

```cyr
if (alloc_used + n > brk_top) {
    var grow = 0x100000;
    if (n > grow) { grow = n + 0x100000; }
    sys_brk(brk_top + grow);
    brk_top = brk_top + grow;
}
```

**Recognize again**: any "alloc(N) for large N silently
SIGSEGVs in subsequent store" shape. Single-store SIGSEGVs
right after an alloc are almost always bump-allocator
boundary issues; print `alloc_used` and `brk_top` at the
crash site to confirm.

Full backstory: v5_6.cyml's
`stdlib_alloc_grow_step_vs_requested_size`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "libssl_needs_fdlopen_not_dynlib_open"
description = "libssl's OPENSSL_init_ssl uses a recursive pthread mutex whose __kind field lives in the glibc TCB. cyrius's dynlib_bootstrap_tls zeroed TCB reads __kind=0 (non-recursive); same-thread re-entry deadlocks on futex. Use lib/fdlopen.cyr (foreign-dlopen) instead."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["dynlib", "tls-loader", "fdlopen", "v5.6.37"]
content = """
**The trap**: cyrius has two ways to load shared libraries at
runtime:

1. `lib/dynlib.cyr` — pure-cyrius ELF .so loader via mmap +
   GNU hash table walk. No libc, no glibc dlopen. Bypasses
   glibc's TLS/TCB setup entirely.

2. `lib/fdlopen.cyr` — foreign-dlopen wrapper. Calls into
   glibc's actual dlopen via the AT_BASE+offset trick, which
   means the loaded library gets glibc's full TLS/TCB setup
   including pthread_*.

For libssl specifically, dynlib_open works for getting symbol
addresses — but calling `OPENSSL_init_ssl()` deadlocks on a
futex inside libcrypto's pthread_mutex_lock. Why: libssl's
init uses `PTHREAD_RECURSIVE_MUTEX_INITIALIZER_NP`. The mutex
struct has a `__kind` field in glibc's TCB. cyrius's
dynlib_bootstrap_tls (the minimal TLS setup that dynlib_open
provides) zeros the TCB. `__kind == 0` means "non-recursive"
in pthread's encoding. Same-thread re-entry to a mutex that
the same thread already holds → futex wait forever (because
non-recursive).

**Rule**: if a library's init function uses pthread mutexes
internally, you NEED fdlopen (real glibc dlopen → real glibc
TLS/TCB), not dynlib (cyrius minimal loader). The list of
libraries that hit this includes:

- libssl (OPENSSL_init_ssl)
- libpthread (everything)
- libgomp (OpenMP runtime)
- libc-internal locking primitives (rare in pure cyrius use,
  but anything that touches TLS-cancellation hooks)

Conversely, dynlib is fine for:

- Pure C libraries with no pthread internals (libz, libcrypto's
  primitive routines if you skip OPENSSL_init_*)
- Libraries you call only for symbol addresses (dlsym then
  call manually)

**Recognize again**: any "dlopen succeeds, dlsym returns valid
pointer, calling that pointer hangs forever" shape on a
shared library that uses pthread mutexes.

Full backstory: v5_6.cyml's `libssl_needs_fdlopen_not_dynlib_open`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "sysv_odd_stack_args_rsp_alignment"
description = "SysV ABI requires rsp 16-aligned at every CALL (so callee sees rsp+8 16-aligned at entry). Cyrius's ECALLPOPS for n>6 args used `add rsp, 48` unconditionally; for odd nextra (N=7,9,11) this left rsp 8-aligned at CALL, propagating misalignment."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["abi", "sysv", "alignment", "v5.6.41"]
content = """
**The trap**: SysV AMD64 ABI requires rsp 16-byte aligned at
every CALL instruction (so the callee sees rsp+8 16-byte
aligned at entry, with the saved rip below it). Cyrius's
codegen for fn calls with >6 args uses ECALLPOPS to clean up
stack arguments after the call:

```cyr
# n > 6 args, n_extra = n - 6
# Push n_extra extra args
# call helper
# add rsp, n_extra * 8  ← cleanup
```

Pre-v5.6.41, the cleanup was `add rsp, n_extra * 8`
unconditionally. For odd `n_extra` (N = 7, 9, 11 args), this
leaves rsp 8-byte-aligned at the next CALL. Misalignment
propagates downstream until something does SSE on a stack-
saved value (libssl/libc prologs commonly do `movdqa xmm,
[rsp+N]`) — SIGSEGV at first instruction.

**Fix**: align rsp to 16 BEFORE pushing extra args:

```cyr
if ((n_extra & 1) == 1) {
    # Pre-pad rsp by 8 to absorb odd n_extra count
    push rax  # any value; we sub rsp, 8 effectively
}
push n_extra args
call helper
add rsp, (n_extra + (n_extra_odd ? 1 : 0)) * 8
```

Win64 path was already correct via framesize-mod-15 alignment
branch; SysV path missed it.

**Recognize again**: any "SIGSEGV on the first SSE instruction
of a libc / libssl entry" shape. Common triggers: 7-arg fn
calls, OpenSSL's EVP_DecryptInit_ex (8 args), recvmmsg
(7 args). Always check rsp alignment via `gdb p $rsp & 0xF`
at the failing instruction.

Full backstory: v5_6.cyml's `sysv_odd_stack_args_rsp_alignment_violation`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "fn_keyword_in_param_position"
description = "`fn` is a reserved keyword and cannot be used as a parameter name even in helper fns. Cyrius surfaces this with 'expected identifier, got reserved keyword fn' at the NEXT fn definition, not the offending one."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["parser", "diagnostics", "v5.7.46"]
content = """
**The trap**: writing `fn helper(fn, arg)` declares a
parameter named `fn`. Cyrius's parser treats `fn` as a
reserved keyword (token type 32), so this fails — but the
error message points at the WRONG location.

The parser first sees `fn helper(`, accepts it, then sees the
parameter list. When it tries to read `fn` as a parameter
name, it errors with "expected identifier, got reserved
keyword fn" — but the PARSE_TOKEN cursor is at the NEXT
function definition's `fn` keyword, not the one in the param
list. So the error reports the line of the next fn, not the
broken param.

Diagnosis is "the fn at line X is broken" → user inspects
line X → finds nothing wrong → confused.

**Fix at v5.7.46** (cyrius v5.5.26+ ERR_EXPECT enhancement):
when the expected token is type 2 (identifier) and the got
token is a keyword (IS_KEYWORD_TOK returns 1), the diagnostic
explicitly names the keyword:

```
error: expected identifier, got reserved keyword 'fn'
       (cannot be used as an identifier; rename the variable/
       field/fn)
```

The error fires at the keyword's actual line, not the next
fn. The "rename" hint helps users figure out the fix without
having to know which keywords are reserved.

**The reserved-keyword list** that triggers this: `fn`, `if`,
`else`, `elif`, `while`, `for`, `return`, `var`, `struct`,
`enum`, `union`, `match`, `defer`, `include`, `asm`, `kernel`,
`object`, `secret`, `in`, `shared`, `default`, `as`,
`continue`, `break`. Any of these as a param/local/struct-
field name surfaces the same error.

**Recognize again**: any "compile error 'expected
identifier' on a line that looks fine" shape. Check the
PREVIOUS fn's param list for keyword reuse.

Full backstory: v5_7.cyml's `fn_keyword_in_param_position`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "lsp_globals_before_fn_definitions"
description = "Cyrius requires top-level `var X` to be declared before any fn body that references X. Applies to programs/cyrius-lsp.cyr's symbol-table backing buffers too."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["compiler", "lsp", "global-init-order", "v5.7.39"]
content = """
**The trap**: cyrius's parser does a single-pass top-down
walk of source. When a fn body references a top-level
`var X`, that `var X` must already be declared at parse time.
Forward fn calls work (the parser pre-scans fn signatures);
forward GLOBAL VAR references DO NOT work.

This is the v5.7.32 cyrlint warning class
(`global-init-order forward-ref`) that mabda surfaced. The
compiler ALSO doesn't catch every shape — the warning is
opt-in via `cyrius lint`.

**The cyrius-lsp specific instance** (v5.7.39): the LSP
extension added cross-file go-to-def + documentSymbol via a
symbol-table backing buffer. The buffer was a top-level `var
symbol_table[N]`. The fns that read it (`SYMBOL_LOOKUP`,
`SYMBOL_INSERT`) were defined before the `var` line in the
source layout.

Pre-fix: the parser saw the fn defs first, registered them,
parsed their bodies → reached `symbol_table` reference →
"undefined variable." Post-fix: moved `var symbol_table[N]`
above all fn defs that reference it.

**Recognize again**: any "undefined variable" error on a top-
level var that VISUALLY appears in the source somewhere.
Check it appears BEFORE the fns that read it.

**Generalize**: any new top-level `var X` declared in
cyrius's own source (or any cyrius project) MUST go above the
fn bodies that reference it. The parser is single-pass for
globals.

Full backstory: v5_7.cyml's `lsp_globals_before_fn_definitions_v5_7_39`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "snapshot_ping_pong_lib_corruption"
description = "lib/*.cyr edits silently revert via install-snapshot copy-back during cyrius deps"
category = "cyrius"
---
Surfaced 2026-05-03 mid-v5.8.23 bite #2 when `lib/tagged.cyr`
edits reverted between Edit calls during the sum-type migration.

== ROOT CAUSE ==

Two-step ping-pong loop:

  1. `version-bump.sh` runs `install.sh --refresh-only` which
     copies `lib/*.cyr` from the repo INTO
     `~/.cyrius/versions/<v>/lib/` and `~/.cyrius/lib`.
  2. Subsequent `cyrius deps` resolution (e.g., during
     `check.sh`) copies the snapshot version BACK into the
     repo.

If you edit a `lib/*.cyr` file AFTER a `version-bump.sh` ran
(snapshot is now stale), the next `check.sh` invocation will
overwrite your edit with the prior snapshot.

== SYMPTOM ==

You make an Edit. You verify the change. You run `check.sh`.
Tests pass. But the next time you read the file, your edit is
GONE. cycc is also gone — the snapshot's version was pulled back
in along with the lib file, AND the snapshot's lib is what's
actually in `~/.cyrius/lib`.

== MITIGATION ==

Documented in CLAUDE.md "Snapshot-ping-pong protection
(cyrius-side `lib/*.cyr` edits)" subsection (added v5.8.26).
3-step recipe:

  1. Edit `lib/<file>.cyr`.
  2. Manually refresh the install snapshot:
     ```sh
     cp lib/<file>.cyr ~/.cyrius/versions/$(cat VERSION)/lib/<file>.cyr
     cp lib/<file>.cyr ~/.cyrius/lib/<file>.cyr
     ```
     OR run `sh scripts/version-bump.sh "$(cat VERSION)"` (same-
     version regenerate path).
  3. Run `sh scripts/check.sh` — file should now stick.

== RELATED ECOSYSTEM RULE ==

CLAUDE.md "Downstream repo setup (ecosystem rule)" forbids
downstream repos (mabda, sigil, sakshi, yukti, etc.) from
symlinking their `lib/` to `~/.cyrius/lib` because writes
through the symlink propagate up the chain into this repo.

Sakshi was found violating this at v5.8.23 (its `lib/` was a
directory-level symlink to `~/.cyrius/lib`); fixed via
`rm sakshi/lib && (cd sakshi && cyrius deps)`.

Audit script (also added to CLAUDE.md v5.8.26):
    find ~/Repos -maxdepth 2 -type l -name lib

Returns nothing now; sakshi was the only directory-level
violation. Other repos have only single-file `lib/<dep>.cyr`
symlinks (legitimate `cyrius deps` artifacts).

[[entries]]
name = "foldin_symlink_vs_regular_file"
description = "When folding a sibling distfile into cyrius's lib/ via the sandhi pattern, the vendored file MUST be a regular file (mode 100644), not the absolute-path symlink that `cyrius deps` creates by default. Symlinks point into the user's local cache (/home/<user>/.cyrius/...) and dangle on any other machine — including CI."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["foldin", "deps", "ci", "sandhi-pattern", "v5.8.65"]
content = """
**The trap**: `cyrius deps` resolves a `[deps.<name>]` entry by
populating `~/.cyrius/deps/<name>/<tag>/` and then creating
`lib/<name>.cyr` as a SYMLINK to that cache path:
```
lib/sakshi.cyr -> /home/<user>/.cyrius/deps/sakshi/2.2.3/dist/sakshi.cyr
```
The symlink target is an ABSOLUTE PATH in the resolving user's
home. On the user's local machine this works because the cache
is populated. On any OTHER machine — including GitHub Actions
CI runners (whose home is `/home/runner/...`) — the symlink
dangles.

When folding a dep into stdlib (sandhi pattern), naive `git
add lib/<name>.cyr` commits the symlink. Git records mode 120000
(symlink). On checkout elsewhere, the symlink resolves against
a non-existent path → file effectively missing.

**Surfaces as**: tcyrs that `include "lib/<name>.cyr"` fail to
compile with "file not found" → cycc exits non-zero → under
`bash -e` (GHA's default shell mode), the test loop terminates
silently mid-loop. No `FAIL:` print, no summary, just exit 1.
Easy to misdiagnose as "test crashed the runner."

**The fix at v5.8.65** (the slot that surfaced this):
1. Convert the symlink to a regular file:
   ```
   cp --remove-destination "$(readlink lib/<name>.cyr)" lib/<name>.cyr
   ```
   `--remove-destination` is essential — `cp` without it follows
   the symlink and writes through to the cache, not the repo.
2. Commit the type change. `git diff` shows mode 120000 → 100644.
3. The cyrius distlib walker (`scripts/lib/audit-walk.sh`) skips
   files matching `^# Generated by: cyrius distlib$` in the first
   5 lines — those byte-snapshot bundles must not be reformatted.
   See also `distlib_marker_styles_v5865`.

**Recognize again**: any time you fold a `[deps.X]` into `lib/`
under the sandhi pattern, audit `git ls-tree HEAD lib/<X>.cyr`
for mode 120000 BEFORE pushing. The v5.7.0 sandhi precedent
(`lib/sandhi.cyr`) is the canonical example — mode 100644,
never a symlink.

**Why it wasn't caught locally**: the user's local machine
HAD the symlink target populated. `check.sh` self-host green,
all 127 tcyrs pass via `cyrius test`. CI is the first place
the absolute path doesn't resolve.

The fix is one shell loop, but the diagnosis took multiple
re-pushes (audit-walk marker fix, then ci.yml inline marker
fan-out, then sakshi-specific bundle.sh marker style). Saved
here so the next foldin slot starts with the de-symlink step
in the playbook.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "distlib_marker_styles_v5865"
description = "Two distlib-bundle marker styles exist in cyrius's vendored lib/: `# Generated by: cyrius distlib` (cyrius distlib output — patra/sigil/vani/yukti/sankoch/agnosys/mabda/sandhi) and `# Bundled distribution of <name>` (sakshi only — its scripts/bundle.sh predates cyrius distlib). audit-walk + ci.yml's stdlib walkers must skip BOTH."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["foldin", "audit-walk", "fmt", "lint", "sakshi", "v5.8.65"]
content = """
**The trap**: `scripts/lib/audit-walk.sh`'s
`_aw_is_distlib_bundle()` and the inline equivalents in
`.github/workflows/ci.yml`'s `Format check (stdlib)` /
`Lint (stdlib)` / `Doc coverage (stdlib)` steps used to match
exactly one marker:
```sh
head -n 5 "$f" 2>/dev/null | grep -q "^# Generated by: cyrius distlib$"
```
When sakshi was folded at v5.8.65, its dist file's header
read:
```
# sakshi.cyr — tracing, error handling, and structured logging
# Bundled distribution of sakshi v2.2.3
```
sakshi builds its dist via its own `scripts/bundle.sh`
predating cyrius's `cyrius distlib` subcommand. Different
header style. The skip-check didn't match → audit-walk ran
`cyrfmt --check` against the vendored bundle, found drift in
some indented `#` comment lines (sakshi-side bundle.sh produces
output whose indent style differs from current cyrfmt's
canonical), and the Format gate failed.

**Wrong fix would be**: apply `cyrfmt --write lib/sakshi.cyr`.
That would make lib/sakshi.cyr DIVERGE from sakshi's
dist/sakshi.cyr — breaking the byte-identity guarantee that's
the whole point of the foldin.

**Right fix**: extend the marker to recognize both styles:
```sh
head -n 5 "$f" 2>/dev/null | \
    grep -qE "^# Generated by: cyrius distlib$|^# Bundled distribution of "
```
Updated in 4 places at v5.8.65: `scripts/lib/audit-walk.sh`'s
`_aw_is_distlib_bundle` + 3 inline call sites in ci.yml
(Format/Lint/Doc-coverage stdlib steps). Mirror comment in
ci.yml notes the audit-walk equivalence so future readers know
they're paired.

**Recognize again**: any new sibling-fold whose dist generator
isn't cyrius distlib needs the marker check audited. The first
few lines of the fold-target's dist file should announce the
generator clearly. If neither `Generated by: cyrius distlib`
nor `Bundled distribution of` appears in the first 5 lines,
add the third marker style at all 4 call sites.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "heap_layout_relocation_option_a_vs_b"
description = "When growing a heap region 8x in-place collides with neighboring scratch state, the choice is Option A (in-place grow + shift downstream — monotonic, ~200+ edits) or Option B (relocate to fresh high block — non-monotonic, ~50 edits). v5.8.46 (tok arrays) + v5.8.59 (str_data) both took Option B; v5.8.61 reverted .59 back to monotonic once the gap was free."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["heap", "layout", "two-step-bootstrap", "v5.8.46", "v5.8.59", "v5.8.61"]
content = """
**The trap**: cyrius's heap regions have hardcoded offset
constants scattered across many files. Growing any region 8x
to absorb new data collides with whatever sits immediately
above. Two paradigms emerge:

**Option A — in-place grow + shift downstream**:
- Region stays at its original offset; size grows.
- Every region above shifts up by the size delta.
- Layout stays MONOTONIC (small-offset → big-offset reads
  cleanly).
- Cost: every offset literal in the affected band updates.
  v5.8.59 estimated this at ~200+ edits across ~20 files for
  the str_data 256 KB → 2 MB grow. Byte-identity risk grows
  linearly with edit count.

**Option B — relocate to fresh high block**:
- Region moves to a new offset above the highest-used heap.
- Size grows in the new location; old slot becomes empty.
- Layout is NON-MONOTONIC (small-offset reads jump past the
  vacant slot to the high block).
- Cost: only the offset literal changes (~50 edits).
- Precedent: v5.8.46 tok-array relocation moved
  tok_types/values/lines from `0x94A000`/`0xD4A000`/`0xF4A000`
  (tangled with output_buf) to a clean post-TS-region high
  block at `0x368C000`/`0x3E8C000`/`0x468C000`.

**The pattern that emerged**: take Option B during the
expansion slot to get the new capacity shipped fast and
audited cheaply. Pin a follow-up "monotonic reorg" slot for
when the layout-non-monotonicity becomes a maintenance
liability. v5.8.59 took Option B to ship NFKC/NFKD via the
str_data bump (placed at `0x4E8C000`); v5.8.61 reverted to
monotonic once the var_enum_id..preprocess_out gap was sized
right (str_data now at `0x21A000`). Two-step bootstrap
required at both: cycc (old layout) compiles cc5b (new layout);
cc5b compiles cc5b'; cc5b == cc5b' byte-identical at the new
size.

**When to use which**:
- New region or major cap raise → Option B initially.
- Cycle wind-down or pre-major-bump → fold back to Option A
  (monotonic) when the receiving gap is the right size.
- DO NOT skip the two-step bootstrap audit for either path —
  heap layout changes are byte-identity-critical.

**Trade-off note**: Option B's non-monotonicity makes future
heap-map readers do mental math (str_data jumped to where?).
The follow-up monotonic reorg pays this back, but only if the
slot pin holds (don't let the "we'll reorg next minor" become
"we'll reorg next major" — pre-v6.0 hardening pin exists for
exactly this drift, see `_aw_is_distlib_bundle` mention in
the heap-map block of src/main.cyr).
"""

[[entries]]
name = "preprocess_out_vs_str_data_caps"
description = "Two distinct heap caps gate compilation. str_data caps the bytes the COMPILER writes for tracked string literals (raised to 2 MB at v5.8.59). preprocess_out caps the bytes of EXPANDED SOURCE the preprocessor produces from include resolution (still 2 MB since v5.6.40). Hitting one isn't the same as hitting the other, and the workarounds are different."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["heap", "preprocessor", "str_data", "v5.8.60"]
content = """
**The trap**: at v5.8.60 (NFKC/NFKD), the original design
used 116-char fixed-width compat-decomp records. 3833 records
× 116 chars = ~445 KB hex-encoded source — well under the
v5.8.59-bumped str_data 2 MB cap. Compiled fine in isolation.

But every consumer tcyr that includes lib/unicode/normalize.cyr
(transitively pulling in _normalize_data.cyr's ~445 KB blob)
also includes the rest of stdlib via auto-prepend. The
*expanded source* — the post-preprocessor concatenation of
all includes — overflowed `preprocess_out` (the 2 MB buffer at
S+0x44A000):
```
error: expanded source exceeds 2MB (2114828 bytes)
```
str_data has plenty of room. preprocess_out is the wall.

**These are two DIFFERENT walls**:
- `str_data` (`0x21A000`, 2 MB at v5.8.61): bytes the compiler
  writes for tracked string literals during codegen. Cap
  applies per-translation-unit.
- `preprocess_out` (`0x44A000`, 2 MB since v5.6.40): bytes of
  the source after include resolution. Cap applies BEFORE the
  lexer even runs.

A consumer that auto-prepends 14 stdlib modules + 6 sibling
distlib modules can sit at 1.6 MB expanded source even before
tcyr-specific code. Adding a 445 KB data table easily blows
the cap.

**The fix at v5.8.60**: switch the data-table encoding from
fixed-width 116-char records (445 KB total) to a 2-table
split — sorted IDX (12 chars/record × 3833 = 46 KB) +
variable-width DATA blob (count + cps, ~41 KB). Total ~87 KB,
80% reduction. Same lookup semantics (binary search IDX → data
offset → read count + cps), but consumer-side preprocess_out
stays well under cap.

**Recognize again**: any new fold-target that adds large
data blobs to lib/ should be sized against BOTH caps:
- Single-file size vs 64 KB string-literal cap (token
  encoding's u16 length field).
- Aggregate across ALL auto-prepended stdlib + the consumer's
  own source vs preprocess_out 2 MB cap.

The 2 MB preprocess_out cap is the easier one to forget
because it's not in the compiler's diagnostic surface during
single-file edits — only manifests when consumers compile.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "install_sh_cp_L_same_file_silent_fail"
description = "install.sh's --refresh-only path uses `cp -L lib/*.cyr` to copy stdlib into snapshot. When lib/<dep>.cyr is a `cyrius deps`-resolved symlink AND the snapshot dir has a parallel symlink to the SAME real file, cp -L exits with 'same file' error. `set -e` makes this fatal — install.sh exits BEFORE the symlink-update block at line 249-251. ~/.cyrius/bin / ~/.cyrius/current stay pointing at the previous version. Discovered v5.10.37."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["cyrius", "install", "deps", "symlink", "set-e", "v5.10.37", "v5.10.46"]
content = """
WHAT BREAKS

After `sh scripts/version-bump.sh 5.10.X`, expected end state:
- `cat ~/.cyrius/current` → 5.10.X
- `readlink ~/.cyrius/bin` → ~/.cyrius/versions/5.10.X/bin
- `~/.cyrius/bin/cycc --version` → cycc 5.10.X

Observed (multi-bump streak in v5.10.x cycle):
- ~/.cyrius/current → stale (5.10.34 e.g.)
- readlink ~/.cyrius/bin → stale version's bin
- cycc --version → stale 5.10.34

User-visible symptom: `cyrius-prompt-info tool` (which reads
through ~/.cyrius/bin/cycc) shows wrong toolchain version on
the user's starship prompt. Easy to mis-read as "starship.toml
corruption" — actual config bytes are intact, but the cyrius
prompt segments render with stale data.

ROOT CAUSE

scripts/install.sh's --refresh-only fast path includes a
lib-copy loop (around line 224):

```sh
while IFS= read -r f; do
    rel="${f#lib/}"
    dst="$CYRIUS_HOME/versions/$VERSION/lib/$rel"
    mkdir -p "$(dirname "$dst")"
    cp -L "$f" "$dst"   # ← FAILS with "same file" for symlink colliders
    _lib_count=$((_lib_count + 1))
done <<EOF_LIB
$(find -L lib -type f -name '*.cyr')
EOF_LIB
```

When `lib/mabda.cyr` is a `cyrius deps`-resolved symlink into
`~/.cyrius/deps/mabda/3.0.0-rc.2/dist/mabda.cyr`, AND the
snapshot at `~/.cyrius/versions/$VERSION/lib/mabda.cyr` is
ALSO a symlink to the same real file (set up by a prior
refresh that ran when the deps target was the same version),
`cp -L` dereferences BOTH and sees source and destination
resolve to the same inode:

```
cp: 'lib/mabda.cyr' and '/home/macro/.cyrius/versions/$VER/lib/mabda.cyr' are the same file
```

install.sh's top-level `set -e` makes this exit code fatal.
The script exits before reaching the symlink-update block:

```sh
# install.sh:249-251 (NEVER RUNS when cp -L fails)
rm -rf "$CYRIUS_HOME/bin" "$CYRIUS_HOME/lib"
ln -sf "$CYRIUS_HOME/versions/$VERSION/bin" "$CYRIUS_HOME/bin"
ln -sf "$CYRIUS_HOME/versions/$VERSION/lib" "$CYRIUS_HOME/lib"
```

So ~/.cyrius/bin / ~/.cyrius/lib / ~/.cyrius/current stay
pointing at whichever version was previously active.

HOW TO DETECT IT MANUALLY

After version-bump.sh, verify:

```sh
test "$(readlink ~/.cyrius/bin | sed 's|.*/versions/||;s|/bin||')" = "$(cat VERSION)" || echo "SYMLINK STALE"
```

If the readlink doesn't match VERSION, install.sh exited
before the symlink dance. Re-run with:

```sh
rm -rf ~/.cyrius/{bin,lib} && \
  ln -sf ~/.cyrius/versions/$(cat VERSION)/bin ~/.cyrius/bin && \
  ln -sf ~/.cyrius/versions/$(cat VERSION)/lib ~/.cyrius/lib && \
  echo "$(cat VERSION)" > ~/.cyrius/current
```

FIX (pinned v5.10.46 closeout)

Two-part fix:
1. **Primary** — change `cyrius deps` to physical-copy
   lib/<dep>.cyr instead of symlinking. Eliminates the
   inode-collision root cause at the architectural layer.
   (Option C from the v5.10.37 user discussion.)
2. **Belt-and-suspenders** — replace `cp -L` with
   `rm -f "$dst" && cp -L` (always nuke dst first) AND add
   a tail-of-refresh-only verification that `readlink
   ~/.cyrius/bin` matches the new version with hard-fail
   if not.

The verification step would have caught this bug in seconds
instead of multiple observations across slots; silent-skip
is the worst kind of failure mode.

LESSON: Install scripts running with `set -e` that perform
multi-step state transitions MUST verify their end-state at
the tail and hard-fail if not consistent. Silent partial-
success is unrecoverable from the user's perspective. The
two version-discovery paths (`cyrius --version` reading
VERSION file directly vs `cyrius-prompt-info tool` reading
through ~/.cyrius/bin/cycc) diverged for multiple version
bumps before anyone noticed.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "cyrius_deps_global_symlink_wedge_v51117"
description = "cyrius deps stdlib_dir resolved from ~/.cyrius/lib (mutable global symlink) before v5.11.17 — wedge for the snapshot-ping-pong wipe"
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["deps", "per-repo-isolation", "v5.11.17", "snapshot-ping-pong"]
---
Surfaced 2026-05-11 at v5.11.3 ship and again at v5.11.13.
Sibling agents (agnosys, mabda, phylax) run `cyriusly use
<other-version>` to test against pinned toolchains; this
flips `~/.cyrius/current` + the `~/.cyrius/bin` /
`~/.cyrius/lib` symlinks. Concurrent `cyrius deps` resolution
in this repo read from the stale snapshot and copied OLD
lib/*.cyr files BACK over in-flight edits.

== ROOT CAUSE ==

`cbt/deps.cyr::_dep_find_stdlib_dir()` resolution order
pre-v5.11.17:

  1. `~/.cyrius/lib` (the global symlink — mutable by ANY
     sibling agent on the dev box)
  2. `./lib` dev-mode fallback

For the cyrius source repo, step 1 ALWAYS won — even though
`./lib` was the actual source of truth. Any sibling-agent
version flip mid-edit triggered the copy-back.

== FIX (v5.11.17) ==

Resolution order rewritten:

  (a) `./lib` if `src/main.cyr` exists (cyrius-repo signal —
      dev-mode preferred; closes the cyrius-repo ping-pong
      since the repo reads from its own in-tree files)
  (b) `~/.cyrius/versions/<cyml-cyrius-field>/lib/` if
      cyrius.cyml's `[package].cyrius = "X.Y.Z"` field is
      set AND that version is installed (per-repo isolation
      for downstream consumers)
  (c) `~/.cyrius/lib` legacy fallback for repos without a
      cyrius pin

Plus: pinned-but-not-installed produces a hard error
(`error: cyrius.cyml pins version X.Y.Z but it is not
installed at <path>; run: cyrius install X.Y.Z`) — never
silent slide to `latest`.

== DETECTION ==

If lib/*.cyr edits revert mid-session AFTER v5.11.17 ship,
investigate:

  1. `cat ~/.cyrius/current` — if not matching `cat VERSION`,
     a sibling agent flipped it (recovery: `cyriusly use
     <correct-version>`).
  2. `find ~/Repos -maxdepth 2 -type l -name lib` — finds
     directory-level lib symlinks (the bad pattern; should
     return empty).
  3. `grep '^cyrius =' cyrius.cyml` — confirms which version
     the repo pins for deps resolution.

Pre-v5.11.17 the recovery dance was: copy lib snapshot back,
re-edit, refresh install snapshot, run check.sh. Post-fix:
just recovery for the `current` symlink flip; lib edits
themselves are protected.

== RELATED ==

See `snapshot_ping_pong_lib_corruption` (v5.8.26 surface) for
the full ping-pong shape. v5.11.17 closes one leg of the
ping-pong; v5.11.24 (per-repo isolation Part 2 — CLI version-
resolved dispatcher) and v5.11.25 (Part 3 — `cyriusly use
--global` flag) will close the others.

[[entries]]
name = "parse_nested_call_string_quirk_var_stage_hint_v51128"
description = "expected ')', got string on nested 2-arg fn-calls inside assert — diagnostic now hints at var-stage workaround"
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["parser", "diagnostic", "fn-args", "var-stage", "v5.11.28", "bote", "v5.11.18"]
---
bote 2.7.1 filed an intermittent `expected ')', got string`
on the shape:

```cyrius
assert(streq(vec_get(caps_v, 0), "fetch") == 1, "msg")
```

i.e. `assert( fn( fn_with_2args(a, b) , LITERAL) == 1,
LITERAL )` — a 2-arg inner call inside another fn-call
inside `assert`. Filing was at cyrius 5.10.34. Trigger was
path-dependent: error position drifted line 187/184/178/173
as preceding lines changed, and after full chunk-by-chunk
re-add the error stopped reproducing — bote couldn't
reliably trigger it even at filing-time. Consumer
workaround: stage the inner call into a `var` first.

== PREMISE-CHECK AT v5.11.28 SLOT ENTRY ==

Reverted bote's `cap0/cap1` var-stage workaround to
recreate the inline-nested shape, compiled at both
v5.11.27 (current) AND v5.10.34 (filing version, intact
at `~/.cyrius/versions/5.10.34/bin/cc5`): clean parse
both times. Synthetic fuzz 0/28 triggers across 9
preceding-line counts (50→240 SSRF-URL asserts before
the trigger) × both versions AND 10 ident counts
(100→10000 filler fns spanning the filing's ~8700
speculation boundary). No reproduction obtainable.

== LIKELY SILENT FIX ==

Commit `f3e98a3e` (first in v5.11.18) doubled the
identifier buffer 131072 → 262144 bytes. This lines up
with the filing's Speculation 2 ("hash collision or
scan-window boundary at ~8700 idents") — capacity
doubling shifts hash-bucket distribution and probe-window
boundaries. Not proof-grade (can't verify without a
repro), but the timing fits the disappearance window.

== WHAT v5.11.28 SHIPS ==

(1) `tests/tcyr/parse_nested_call_assert.tcyr` (13 asserts)
locks the nested-call shape — bote's exact trigger,
3-deep nested variant, and the same shape preceded by a
7-assert SSRF-URL + JSON-literal stress block
approximating bote's ~180-line preceding context. Future
parser refactors that reintroduce the state leak surface
in this file.

(2) `src/common/util.cyr:425-432` adds a hint to
`ERR_EXPECT` when surface is `expected ')'` or
`expected ','` AND got-token is a string literal:

```
error:<source>:N: expected ')', got string
  hint: a string literal where ')' is expected often means
        a nested call inside a fn argument confused the
        parser; stage the inner call into a `var` first.
```

The hint sits between the diagnostic line and the existing
capacity dump, so consumers see "stage to var" before they
start re-balancing quotes or escapes. The filing
explicitly called out the misleading-diagnostic burden
("the `expected ')', got string` symptom sends consumers
down the wrong rabbit hole") as the part worth fixing
even when the underlying bug is intermittent.

== LESSON ==

A misleading diagnostic earns its own slot-share even when
the underlying bug is unreproducible. The bote filing
spent ~45 minutes of bisect before the var-stage rescue
became obvious; one hint string saves that future-time
for every consumer whose parse fails this shape, whether
the original state-leak is still live or not.

[[entries]]
name = "elf64_kernel_fixup_entry_mismatch_v51146"
description = "FIXUP's kmode==1 hard-coded entry=0x100060 (ELF32+mb1 layout) while EMITELF64_KERNEL writes code at 0x1000A8 (ELF64+mb2 layout). 0x48-byte fixup shift produced garbled serial after GRUB-EFI handoff on agnos. Fix: gate FIXUP's kmode==1 entry on _TARGET_ELF64_KERNEL"
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["compiler", "fixup", "elf64", "multiboot2", "agnos", "v5.11.43", "v5.11.46", "cross-emitter-invariant"]
---
v5.11.43 shipped `EMITELF64_KERNEL` (ELF64 + multiboot2
+ EFI64-entry tag) at `src/backend/x86/fixup.cyr:873`,
gated by env var `CYRIUS_ELF64_KERNEL=1` flipping
`_TARGET_ELF64_KERNEL`. The new emitter writes code at
file offset `120 + 48 = 168` (ELF64 hdr 64 + PH64 56 +
multiboot2 48), so `e_entry = 0x100000 + 168 = 0x1000A8`.

But `FIXUP()` at the same file's line 95 hardcoded
`entry = 0x100060` for `kmode == 1` (legacy ELF32 +
multiboot1 layout: `0x100000 + 84 + 12`). Every absolute
fixup was computed with `dbase = entry + acp`, so every
baked address was 0x48 = 72 bytes earlier than the
actual symbol location. The classic shape:

```cyrius
mov rcx, 0x1001D8    ; FIXUP baked this address
                     ; ...but string lives at 0x100220
```

A `mov rcx, 0x1001D8` lands inside the multiboot2
header bytes instead of the actual `.rodata` string.
After GRUB-EFI handoff, the kernel reads garbage as
the string pointer → garbled VGA / serial output.

== EMPIRICAL CONFIRMATION (v5.11.46) ==

Compiled `programs/kernel_hello.cyr` with pre-fix
`build/cc5` (v5.11.45) + `CYRIUS_KERNEL=1
CYRIUS_ELF64_KERNEL=1`:

- ELF64 `e_entry` (header, offset 24): **`0x1000A8`** ✓
  (EMITELF64_KERNEL writes this correctly)
- `"Hello from Cyrius!"` string at file offset `0x220`
  → true VA `0x100220`
- Baked address inside `.text` at file offset `0x1FE`:
  **`0x1001D8`** = `0x100220 - 0x48` (FIXUP's bug)

The header was self-consistent (EMITELF64_KERNEL did
its own arithmetic correctly); the FIXUP-baked
addresses were 72 B off because FIXUP didn't know
about ELF64-kernel mode.

== FIX SHAPE ==

`src/backend/x86/fixup.cyr:95`:

```cyrius
if (kmode == 1) {
    entry = 0x100000 + 84 + 12;
    if (_TARGET_ELF64_KERNEL == 1) {
        entry = 0x100000 + 120 + 48;
    }
}
```

The expanded form (vs the prior literal `0x100060`)
keeps the arithmetic visibly tied to the same layout
numbers EMITELF_KERNEL + EMITELF64_KERNEL use
internally — future drift between the three sites is
grep-detectable.

== CROSS-EMITTER INVARIANT ==

The general lesson: **every code-emitter that depends
on a header-emitter's layout must consume the same
layout constants, not reinvent them**. cyrius has 5
ELF emitters (x86 user, x86 kernel ELF32+mb1, x86
kernel ELF64+mb2, aarch64 user, aarch64 kernel) and
each must agree on entry-RVA with FIXUP's absolute-
address computation. The v5.11.29-34 section-header
parity sweep was a sibling instance of the same class:
fix one emitter, miss the other 4 silently.

== REGRESSION GATE ==

`_elf64_kernel_entry_gate()` in `programs/check.cyr`
locks the invariant: compiles `kernel_hello.cyr` with
`CYRIUS_KERNEL=1 CYRIUS_ELF64_KERNEL=1`, asserts ELF64
magic + `e_entry == 0x1000A8`, locates the
`"Hello from Cyrius!"` string, computes its true VA
from `p_vaddr + file_offset`, asserts the OLD-entry-
shifted pattern (`true_va - 0x48`) is **absent**
anywhere in the binary, asserts the true-VA pattern
is present at least once (positive sanity). Negative-
test verified at slot time: pre-fix cc5 produces the
`FAIL: OLD-entry-shifted address 1049048 at file
offset 510` diagnostic with exact-match numbers.

== FILING CONTEXT — PROCESS PIN ==

This bug existed because an unauthorized cross-repo
edit hit `src/backend/x86/fixup.cyr` from an
agnosticos agent working on AGNOS boot. Patch was
technically correct; **the process violation is the
load-bearing reason for the v5.11.45 revert**, not
the technical content. Cyrius does not accept drive-by
patches from sibling-repo agents even when 100%
correct. Project leader pinned (2026-05-13): "EVEN
IF ITS 100% CORRECT THE VIOLATION IS THE PROBLEM ...
FIRABLE OFFENCE IN REAL LIFE IS MY ISSUE." The filing
form is: file as `docs/development/issues/YYYY-MM-DD-<short>.md`
in cyrius repo, not patch. Cyrius-side investigator
implements through cyrius's own slot lifecycle. See
memory pin `feedback_no_unauthorized_cross_repo_edits`.

[[entries]]
name = "relocs_stripped_vs_ovmf_v51149"
description = "OVMF firmware treats COFF Characteristics RELOCS_STRIPPED (0x0001) as 'load at exact ImageBase or fail'. UEFI Application binaries must NEVER set this bit, even with zero actual fixups. Standard UEFI loaders (rEFInd, systemd-boot, GRUB-EFI) all clear it"
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["compiler", "pe", "uefi", "ovmf", "efi-application", "relocs-stripped", "coff-characteristics", "v5.11.49", "gnoboot", "silent-rejection"]
---
v5.11.48 shipped EFI Application emit (`_TARGET_EFI_APPLICATION
== 1` via `CYRIUS_TARGET_EFI=1` env var) that produced
a structurally-correct PE32+: Subsystem=0xA, NX_COMPAT,
Data Dirs [1]/[12] zeroed, `.text` with single-byte
`ret` EEXIT. The structural gate `_efi_emit_gate()`
asserted all of those green.

At .49 entry, manual OVMF runtime smoke:

```
BdsDxe: loading Boot0002 "UEFI QEMU HARDDISK QM00001 "
        from PciRoot(0x0)/Pci(0x1F,0x2)/Sata(0x0,0xFFFF,0x0)
BdsDxe: failed to load Boot0002 "UEFI QEMU HARDDISK QM00001 "
        ...: Not Found
BdsDxe: No bootable option or device was found.
```

Firmware found the GPT disk + ESP partition + the
file at `\EFI\BOOT\BOOTX64.EFI` (verified via mdir
into the FAT image: content byte-identical to the
compile output). But BdsDxe rejected the load and
reported "Not Found" with no indication of *why*.

== ROOT CAUSE ==

COFF Characteristics field at PE header offset
`pe_off + 4 + 18`:

```python
chars = 0x0023 = 0b0000_0000_0010_0011
                            │      ││
                            │      │└─ EXECUTABLE_IMAGE (0x0002)
                            │      └── RELOCS_STRIPPED (0x0001) ← THIS
                            └──────── LARGE_ADDRESS_AWARE (0x0020)
```

Per the PE/COFF spec, `RELOCS_STRIPPED` declares
"this image's relocations are stripped — the loader
MUST load me at exactly ImageBase or fail." Cyrius
emits with `ImageBase = 0x140000000`. Under OVMF
firmware, the runtime services occupy nearby pages in
firmware's memory map; OVMF's PE loader can't allocate
0x140000000 → BdsDxe silently rejects the image →
reports "Not Found" with no further detail.

The trap: structural correctness of the PE headers
isn't enough. Standard UEFI Application binaries
(rEFInd, systemd-boot, GRUB-EFI, the EDK2 sample
apps) **never** set RELOCS_STRIPPED. Cyrius's PE
backend was setting it by default at
`src/backend/pe/emit.cyr:714` and only clearing it
when `.reloc` had content (`_pe_reloc_vsize != 0`).
A zero-fixup probe-style EFI program (no globals,
no DIR64 entries, no `.reloc`) kept RELOCS_STRIPPED
set → silent rejection on every UEFI firmware that
can't honor ImageBase.

== FIX SHAPE ==

`src/backend/pe/emit.cyr:714` — branch unconditionally
on `_TARGET_EFI_APPLICATION`:

```cyrius
var _chars = 0x0023;
if (_pe_reloc_vsize != 0) { _chars = 0x0022; }
if (_TARGET_EFI_APPLICATION == 1) { _chars = 0x0022; }
```

UEFI mode now clears RELOCS_STRIPPED regardless of
whether `.reloc` is empty. Firmware can place the
image at any free address; the probe doesn't care
(all addressing is runtime register-indirect — no
imm64 references); gnoboot will care correctly once
it has globals (covered by `.reloc` which fires
naturally when DIR64 fixups exist).

Post-fix boot trace:

```
BdsDxe: starting Boot0002 "UEFI QEMU HARDDISK QM00001 " ...
hello, uefi
BdsDxe: loading Boot0000 "BootManagerMenuApp" ...
```

Firmware loaded BOOTX64.EFI, jumped to
AddressOfEntryPoint, our inline-asm ran
`SystemTable→ConOut→OutputString(L"hello, uefi\\r\\n")`,
returned EFI_SUCCESS, firmware unwound back to boot
manager menu. **End-to-end working.**

== REGRESSION GATE ==

`_efi_ovmf_smoke_gate()` in `programs/check.cyr`
runtime-floors this: builds GPT disk + ESP + boots
qemu+OVMF with `-serial stdio` capture + greps for
`"hello, uefi"`. Graceful SKIP if qemu / parted /
mtools / OVMF firmware files absent. Negative-test
verified at slot time: with pre-.49 cc5 (RELOCS_STRIPPED
still set), gate FAILs `(sh rc=1)`; post-fix → PASS.

== LESSON FOR FUTURE EMITTER WORK ==

**Structural correctness is necessary but not
sufficient when firmware silently rejects.** OVMF's
"Not Found" was actively misleading — the firmware
was telling us the *outcome* (couldn't load) without
the *cause* (RELOCS_STRIPPED contract violation). The
only way to catch this class of bug is runtime smoke,
not structural inspection. The v5.11.49 OVMF smoke
gate is the runtime-floor that catches RELOCS_STRIPPED
or any future analogous silent-rejector.

Reference: PE/COFF spec § 5.1 (Characteristics);
UEFI 2.10 spec § 2.3.4.1 (LoadImage behavior on
non-relocatable images).

[[entries]]
name = "pe_entry_prologue_e9_jmp_zero_preserves_gpr_v51148"
description = "cyrius PE entry emits e9 00 00 00 00 (5-byte jmp +0) at AddressOfEntryPoint before user code. The jmp touches no GPRs, so RCX/RDX/R8/R9 (MS x64 first 4 args) survive into the first user instruction. Inline-asm-first is the right shape for capturing UEFI firmware-supplied args"
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["compiler", "pe", "entry-point", "ms-x64-abi", "uefi", "inline-asm", "v5.11.48", "register-preservation"]
---
While scoping `programs/efi_probe.cyr` at v5.11.48 entry,
the question was: where in cyrius's PE entry does user
code start, and do RCX/RDX (firmware-supplied
ImageHandle / SystemTable per the UEFI MS x64 ABI)
survive long enough for user code to capture them?

== EMPIRICAL ANSWER ==

Compiled a probe with a distinctive 4-NOP marker as
the FIRST user inline-asm:

```cyrius
kernel;
asm { 0x90; 0x90; 0x90; 0x90; }   # marker
asm { 0x48; 0x89; 0xC8; }          # mov rax, rcx
var result = 42;
```

Compiled with `CYRIUS_TARGET_EFI=1` and inspected
`.text` from the AddressOfEntryPoint:

```
.text first 24 bytes: e9 00 00 00 00 90 90 90 90 48 89 c8 b8 2a 00 00 00 48 b9 ...
                      └─ prologue ─┘ └─ 4 NOPs ─┘ └─ mov rax,rcx ─┘ └─ var init ...
```

The 4-NOP marker landed at `.text + 0x05` (after the
5-byte cyrius prologue `e9 00 00 00 00` = `jmp +0`).

== WHY THE PROLOGUE PRESERVES GPRS ==

`jmp rel32` writes only RIP — no flags, no GPRs, no
memory. Even when `disp32 == 0` (a 5-byte effective
no-op), it remains a register-preserving instruction.
So firmware-supplied RCX (ImageHandle), RDX
(SystemTable), R8, R9 (the MS x64 first 4 args, also
the UEFI calling convention) all survive intact into
the first byte of user code.

== WHY FN CALLS DO NOT PRESERVE GPRS ==

Cyrius's normal fn-call emit shape (MS x64 ABI under
`_TARGET_PE == 1`) emits arg-setup before the call:

```
mov rcx, <arg1>    ; clobbers ImageHandle
mov rdx, <arg2>    ; clobbers SystemTable
call <fn>
```

If user code calls *any* fn before capturing RCX/RDX,
the firmware-supplied values are lost. So "capture
RCX/RDX via inline asm before any fn call" is the
required entry shape for UEFI Applications written
in cyrius.

== THE EFI_PROBE PATTERN ==

`programs/efi_probe.cyr` (v5.11.48) uses a single
`asm { ... }` block as the entire program body —
no globals (no fixups → no DIR64 → minimal `.reloc`),
no fn calls (no GPR clobbering), runtime register-
indirect addressing only. The asm walks
`SystemTable → ConOut → OutputString` and embeds the
UTF-16 message bytes inline at the end of the block,
addressed via RIP-relative LEA with a hand-computed
displacement. ~30 bytes of code + 28 bytes of message
+ 1 NOP for 2-byte CHAR16 alignment.

This pattern is the lower-bound shape for any future
cyrius UEFI app that needs to keep firmware args
alive. gnoboot will use a heavier shape (it has
globals, fns, allocator) but the initial argument
capture has to be inline-asm-first.

== ALTERNATIVE NOT TAKEN ==

A "tinified fn prologue" approach (preserve RCX/RDX
via inline asm at entry, then call a regular fn with
the captured values) was considered but rejected:
inline-asm support for emitting a fixup-aware
`mov reg, &global` would require compiler work
(cyrius's `asm { 0xXX; }` byte-emit doesn't have a
fixup-record hook). For the .48 MVP probe, the
single-asm-block shape works because everything is
register-indirect. A future slot may add fixup-aware
inline asm if/when gnoboot needs it.

[[entries]]
name = "dll_characteristics_nx_compat_zero_fixup_efi_v51148"
description = "v5.6.31 set DllCharacteristics = 0x0160 (NX_COMPAT + DYNAMIC_BASE + HIGH_ENTROPY_VA) only when .reloc was present. Zero-fixup EFI binaries (probe-style) had DllChar = 0x0000 with no NX_COMPAT, which UEFI 2.0+ may reject. Fix: EFI mode forces NX_COMPAT bit (0x0100) regardless of .reloc presence"
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["compiler", "pe", "dll-characteristics", "nx-compat", "uefi", "v5.11.48", "efi-application", "memory-attributes-protocol"]
---
The v5.6.31 logic at `src/backend/pe/emit.cyr:776`:

```cyrius
var _dllc = 0;
if (_pe_reloc_vsize != 0) { _dllc = 0x0160; }
```

set DllCharacteristics to `0x0160` (NX_COMPAT 0x0100 +
DYNAMIC_BASE 0x0040 + HIGH_ENTROPY_VA 0x0020) **only**
when `.reloc` was present. For Windows-CUI consumers
with at least one global (almost always true), this
shipped the bits the security audits wanted.

For an EFI Application probe that uses no globals (no
DIR64 entries → no `.reloc` content → `_pe_reloc_vsize
== 0`), DllCharacteristics = `0x0000`. UEFI 2.0+
firmware honors NX on code pages via the Memory
Attributes Protocol; without `NX_COMPAT` (0x0100) set,
some firmware implementations refuse to invoke the
image (mark `.text` as no-execute and trap on entry).

== FIX SHAPE (v5.11.48) ==

```cyrius
var _dllc = 0;
if (_pe_reloc_vsize != 0) { _dllc = 0x0160; }
if (_TARGET_EFI_APPLICATION == 1 && _pe_reloc_vsize == 0) {
    _dllc = 0x0100;   # NX_COMPAT only
}
```

EFI mode + zero fixups now forces NX_COMPAT alone.
DYNAMIC_BASE stays off because the image is
non-relocatable (no `.reloc`); firmware honors
ImageBase = 0x140000000 directly. EFI programs with
at least one global fixup get the full `0x0160` from
the existing v5.6.31 branch (.reloc present →
relocatable → DYNAMIC_BASE meaningful → HIGH_ENTROPY_VA
meaningful too).

== CROSS-REFERENCE ==

This is the **second** silent-rejection class hit by
the v5.11.49 OVMF runtime smoke. The first was
RELOCS_STRIPPED (see `relocs_stripped_vs_ovmf_v51149`
entry above). Both required runtime testing to surface
— structural inspection alone would have missed both.

== HIGH_ENTROPY_VA NOTE ==

The v5.5.35 comment block in `pe/emit.cyr` documents
that HIGH_ENTROPY_VA (0x0020) was empirically observed
to break cc5_win.exe's stdin read on Win11 (5/5 runs).
That failure does NOT apply under UEFI — firmware
doesn't have stdin in the Windows sense; OutputString
+ runtime services are unaffected. The `0x0160` for
EFI mode with `.reloc` present is safe; the Win11
stdin issue is Windows-only.

[[entries]]
name = "build_cc5_silent_contamination_recurrence_v51144"
description = "build/cc5 has been silently overwritten with non-cyrius binaries multiple times across v5.11.x — at v5.11.28/.29 (silently fixed .30) and again at v5.11.43 (a 1.39 MB binary containing mabda/wgpu/compute-pipeline strings). install.sh --refresh-only carries the contamination into ~/.cyrius/bin/cc5. v5.11.45 added a grep gate"
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["compiler", "build", "contamination", "release-process", "v5.11.43", "v5.11.44", "v5.11.45", "mabda", "wgpu", "fail-fast-gate"]
---
v5.11.44 caught a P0 build artifact: the committed
`build/cc5` at v5.11.43 (commit `aad19f6a` EMIT64KERNEL)
was a **1,389,776 B binary containing mabda/wgpu/
compute-pipeline strings — NOT the cyrius compiler**.

`git diff aad19f6a -- src/ lib/` was empty;
current `src/` self-hosted byte-identical to the
canonical 821,712 B at v5.11.43 / 821,984 B at .44.
v5.11.41's cc5 fed current `src/main.cyr` also produced
821,712 B. So the source was clean; only `build/cc5`
was wrong.

== RECURRENCE PATTERN ==

Same shape contamination at v5.11.28/.29, silently
fixed at .30 with no postmortem at the time. Recurred
at .43 → caught at .44.

Most likely cause: a build script during the .43
prep cp'd another binary (a mabda-built binary that
happened to be in the build directory or in a sibling
repo's `build/`) over `build/cc5` immediately before
the commit. `install.sh --refresh-only` then carried
the contamination into `~/.cyrius/bin/cc5` +
`~/.cyrius/versions/5.11.43/bin/cc5` (both 1,389,776 B
mabda carryovers verified at .44 ship).

== WHY IT'S HARD TO DETECT NORMALLY ==

The contamination is invisible to `cyrius test` and
self-host verify if you happen to run them through
the OLD cc5 in `~/.cyrius/bin/`. The new
`build/cc5` is what's broken, but the install-snapshot
shim might re-symlink to a previous-version's cc5
if its mtime check skips the rebuild. Layered
silent-fail until somebody actually pipes
`src/main.cyr` through the committed `build/cc5`.

== FIX (v5.11.45) ==

New `_cc5_contamination_gate()` in
`programs/check.cyr` (v5.11.45 P(-1) hardening bundle).
Greps `build/cc5` for `mabda: gpu` / `wgpuDevice` /
`compute_pipeline` substrings — the v5.11.43-style
slip signature. Fails check.sh fast. Negative test
verified: tainting `build/cc5` makes the gate FAIL;
restoring → PASS.

== PROCESS PIN (CLOSEOUT-CANDIDATE) ==

The CLAUDE.md closeout pass should include a
`strings build/cc5 | grep -E "mabda|wgpu|compute_pipeline"`
check before any version-bump commits. v6.0.0
closeout will be the natural place to lift this from
"gate that catches it after commit" to "pre-commit
hook that refuses to commit a contaminated cc5".

== ADJACENT SLIP: cyrius vet AT v5.11.45 ==

The same v5.11.45 P(-1) hardening bundle caught a
parallel slip in `build/cyrc`: had been silently
replaced with the 12 KB bootstrap binary instead of
the real audit tool. install.sh `_rebuild_stale`
skipped the rebuild because the bad binary's mtime
was newer than source — same shape of silent-fail
as build/cc5's mabda contamination. Fixed by adding
an explicit `syscall(60, r)` exit to
`programs/cyrc.cyr` (vet was running twice — module
init + runtime fall-through), and raising the
scan-buffer cap 16 KB → 256 KB (was truncating reads
on 86 KB source files and falsely reporting "no
dependencies"). cyrc 12,344 B (bootstrap) → 44,672 B
(real audit tool).

== LESSON ==

`build/<binary>` mtime-based rebuild logic in
`install.sh` is a silent-fail surface. Any committed
build artifact should have a content-integrity check
(strings-grep, byte-pattern, ELF-magic — whatever is
cheap and specific) rather than relying on mtime
comparisons against source. v6.0.0 closeout should
generalize the .45 contamination gate to cover every
committed `build/<binary>` artifact, not just cc5.


[[entries]]
name = "gvar_init_order_kmode_static_v51164"
description = "kmode==1 emit order puts gvar-init AFTER PARSE_PROG which never returns. Top-level `var X = INT_LITERAL ;` declarations got their runtime store CODE-EMITTED but never EXECUTED. agnos's XHCI_CMD_TIMEOUT_SPINS = 10000000 read as 0. v5.11.64 fixed via static-init tables (gvar_initval + gvar_byte_off) baking literal values into file image at FIXUP-time."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["compiler", "kmode", "gvar", "agnos", "kernel", "static-init", "fixup", "v5.11.64"]
content = """
== SYMPTOM ==

agnos kernel main body reads a top-level gvar as 0 even
though source declares `var XHCI_CMD_TIMEOUT_SPINS =
10000000;`. Helper fn `_xhci_wait_command()` consumes the
value as a spin-loop iteration count; gets 0; loops never
execute; xHCI commands time out. 10+ iron-burn debug
attempts before the compiler-side root cause surfaced.

== ROOT CAUSE ==

In `kmode==1` mode (kernel target), cyrius emit order is:

  [boot-shim asm]
  → [rest of PARSE_PROG]
  → [EMIT_GVAR_INITS]   # the runtime stores

The boot-shim asm + PARSE_PROG body produce the kernel
mainline that NEVER RETURNS (kernel main is an infinite
event loop). EMIT_GVAR_INITS emits AFTER the mainline.
The code is in the binary but unreachable.

So the runtime store sequence `mov rax, 10000000; mov
[gvar_X_addr], rax` is generated correctly — but the CPU
never executes it. The gvar reads return the BSS-zero
default instead of the declared literal.

== WHY THIS DIDN'T BITE EARLIER ==

Pre-v5.11.x agnos consumers used compile-time constants
(enum variants, #define macros) for the kernel-mainline
parameters. The first agnos slot to declare a top-level
`var X = N;` for a magic number was the xHCI sub-arc —
which surfaced the bug.

Userland binaries don't hit this: `main()` RETURNS (to
exit syscall stub); EMIT_GVAR_INITS lands BEFORE main
in userland-emit order; gvars get initialized before
main runs.

== FIX (v5.11.64) ==

PARSE_GVAR_REG detects `= INT_LITERAL ;` shape with
positive non-zero RHS:

1. Records value in new `gvar_initval` table at
   0x1EC000 (8192 × 8B; uses freed `fn_ret_sid` slot
   relocated to 0x15A000 at v5.11.19).
2. SKIPS gvar_toks registration so EMIT_GVAR_INITS
   doesn't replay the runtime store.

FIXUP populates per-var byte offsets in stable
`gvar_byte_off` mirror at 0x1B0000 (8192 × 8B prefix-sum
mirror, FIXUP-time written / EMIT-time read).

Each EMIT_* path adds `_EMIT_GVAR_STATIC_INITS(S, O, bss_o)`
after its var-area zero-fill to S64 literal bytes at the
right offsets. Result: value is in the file image at first
read; no runtime store needed.

== CROSS-ARCH COVERAGE ==

Every EMIT_* that writes a var area to file:
- x86 EMITELF_KERNEL + EMITELF64_KERNEL + EMITELF_USER +
  EMITELF_SHARED + EMITELF_OBJ
- aarch64 EMITELF + EMITELF_KERNEL
- MachO x86_64 + ARM64 (ARM64 guarded by has_data == 1)
- PE EMITPE_EXEC (handles both Windows EXE + EFI Application)

cx bytecode opts OUT via `_TARGET_CX != 1` guard in
PARSE_GVAR_REG.

== SHADOW-DECLARATION OPT-OUT ==

When FINDVAR finds an existing match for the new var name
(shadow redecl), fall through to runtime-store. Caught
during bring-up by `math_constants.tcyr`: mabda's `var
F64_TWO = 0` shadowed by math's `var F64_TWO =
0x4000_0000_0000_0000` hit EMIT_GVAR_INITS's FINDVAR-last-
match semantics — mabda's runtime-store-of-zero targeted
math's address, clobbering the new static-init bytes.

== cc5 SIZE DELTA ==

cc5 SHRANK 875,336 → 872,952 B (-2,384 B) from eliminating
runtime stores for cc5's own TS_TOK_* literal gvars in
src/frontend/ts/. Static-init eliminates the per-gvar
`mov rax, imm64; mov [addr], rax` sequence (~11 bytes per
gvar) and replaces with file-image bytes (8 bytes per gvar
in the .data section). Net savings depends on gvar count
in the compiler's own source.

== LESSON ==

Any compiler-emit ordering that places initialization
AFTER an unreachable code path is a silent-fail. The fix
shape "bake value into file image at FIXUP-time" is the
right pattern for kmode-shaped consumers (kernels, EFI
apps, anything where main never returns). The pattern is
also CHEAPER (smaller binary) than runtime stores.

For agents debugging "gvar reads 0 in kernel mode":
1. `objdump -d` the binary; find the gvar's address.
2. Check whether EMIT_GVAR_INITS sequence appears BEFORE
   or AFTER kernel main's entry. If after, static-init
   wasn't applied — confirm `gvar_initval[]` was populated.
3. Common cause: shadow-redecl where FINDVAR returned a
   different gvar's slot. Check both source files for
   the same var name at module scope.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "cve_05_tok_names_mangle_magic_budget_v51165"
description = "NPOS_GUARD(S, 256) was a magic-pessimistic budget that source-identifier byte-copy loops could SILENTLY exceed. tok_names region (256 KB @ 0x60000) could overflow into adjacent regions if source identifier + separator + dest identifier > 256 bytes. Worse: 4 of 6 main_*.cyr variants had NO tok_names guard at all on the use-alias mangle path. v5.11.65 replaced magic-256 with compute-source-length-then-NPOS_GUARD across 11 sites."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["compiler", "tok_names", "mangle-path", "cve-05", "security", "cross-arch", "v5.11.65"]
content = """
== SYMPTOM ==

`docs/audit/2026-04-13-security-audit.md` § CVE-05 flagged
"Heap region overlap — no guard pages" as a P1: write-side
checks for str_data / tok_names / codebuf were the fix
direction. CVE-06 covered str_data at v5.x; codebuf was
covered by EB() on both arches. The remaining gap was
tok_names.

== ROOT CAUSE ==

`NPOS_GUARD(S, need)` in `src/frontend/lex.cyr` checks
`np + need >= 261872` and exits cleanly on overflow. The
`need` argument is supposed to be a pessimistic byte count
for the pending write. 11 mangle-path call sites used
`NPOS_GUARD(S, 256)` as a MAGIC PESSIMISTIC BUDGET:

  fn BUILD_METHOD_NAME(S, si, mnoff): i64 {
      NPOS_GUARD(S, 256);                       // LIES: budget is 256
      var scratch = GNPOS(S);
      var wp = scratch;
      var snoff = L64(S + 0x18E630 + si * 8);
      var ri = 0;
      var rc = load8(S + 0x60000 + snoff + ri);
      while (rc != 0) {                         // unbounded copy
          store8(S + 0x60000 + wp, rc);
          wp = wp + 1; ri = ri + 1;
          rc = load8(S + 0x60000 + snoff + ri);
      }
      // ... separator + method name + null ...
  }

If `struct_name_len + 1 + method_name_len + 1 > 256`, the
write loop exceeds the guard's promise. Source identifiers
can be up to tok_names region cap (262144 bytes), so the
guard's pessimistic budget didn't actually cover the
realistic shape.

In practice the bug rarely bit because typical identifiers
are < 256 bytes. But it's a SILENT overflow — corruption
would land in adjacent regions (struct_*, fn_*, etc.) and
cause downstream miscompile / parse error with no
diagnostic.

== WORSE PRE-EXISTING GAP ==

The 4 non-x86 main_*.cyr variants (aarch64,
aarch64_macho, aarch64_native, cx) had **no prior
tok_names guard at all** on the use-alias path:

  // main_aarch64.cyr — pre-v5.11.65
  S64(S + 0x18FFD0 + uc * 8, ufn);
  var apos = GNPOS(S);                          // NO NPOS_GUARD CALL
  var ri = 0;
  var rc = load8(S + 0x60000 + umod + ri);
  while (rc != 0) { ... }

The parallel x86 main.cyr had the magic-256 NPOS_GUARD
that the cross-arch variants never gained — caught at the
audit-at-slot-entry sweep, not in the original v5.11.18
NPOS_GUARD introduction.

== FIX (v5.11.65) ==

Pre-walk source identifier strlen(s); pass actual sum to
NPOS_GUARD:

  fn BUILD_METHOD_NAME(S, si, mnoff): i64 {
      var snoff = L64(S + 0x18E630 + si * 8);
      var _snlen = 0;
      while (load8(S + 0x60000 + snoff + _snlen) != 0) {
          _snlen = _snlen + 1;
      }
      var _mnlen = 0;
      while (load8(S + 0x60000 + mnoff + _mnlen) != 0) {
          _mnlen = _mnlen + 1;
      }
      NPOS_GUARD(S, _snlen + 1 + _mnlen + 1);   // ACTUAL write size
      // ... rest unchanged ...
  }

NPOS_GUARD's existing region cap check (`np + need >=
261872`) now bounds the ACTUAL write surface, not a lying
magic budget.

== 11 SITES FIXED ==

- parse_decl.cyr — BUILD_METHOD_NAME (struct + method)
- parse_expr.cyr — BUILD_OP_NAME (struct + op_str)
- parse_fn.cyr — PARSE_FN_DEF module-mangle (mmod + noff)
- parse_types.cyr — variant-ctor mangle × 2 (pass 1 + 2)
- main.cyr — use-alias mangle (umod + ufn)
- main_aarch64.cyr — use-alias mangle (added guard from
  scratch)
- main_aarch64_macho.cyr — use-alias mangle (added guard
  from scratch)
- main_aarch64_native.cyr — use-alias mangle (added guard
  from scratch)
- main_cx.cyr — use-alias mangle (added guard from scratch)
- main_win.cyr — use-alias mangle

== STRUCTURAL GATE ==

`programs/check.cyr::_cve05_guard_gate()` greps the 10
affected source files for `NPOS_GUARD(S, 256)` and fails
fast on any reappearance. Negative-tested at slot bring-up
(manual sed-inject of the magic-256 pattern → gate FAIL;
restore → gate PASS). check.sh 75 → 76.

== EXISTING PRECEDENT ==

`parse_expr.cyr::EMIT_OVF_CALL` was already doing the
correct pattern at v5.6.x:

  fn EMIT_OVF_CALL(S, fname_str): i64 {
      var flen = 0;
      while (load8(fname_str + flen) != 0) { flen = flen + 1; }
      NPOS_GUARD(S, flen + 1);                  // compute then guard
      // ... rest ...
  }

The .65 fix propagated this pattern to the 11 other call
sites that hadn't adopted it.

== LESSON ==

Any "pessimistic budget" passed to a bounds-check helper
where the actual write size depends on input data is a
LATENT silent overflow. The fix shape — strlen the input
first, then call the guard with the actual size — adds
~5 LoC per site but eliminates the silent-overflow class.

For agents writing future tok_names-writing code:
1. Walk source identifier(s) with `while load8 != 0`.
2. Sum: `len_a + 1 + len_b + 1 + ...` for each component
   (separator + null terminator counts).
3. Call `NPOS_GUARD(S, actual_sum)`.

DO NOT use `NPOS_GUARD(S, MAGIC_CONSTANT)` for any write
shape where the input length depends on parser state.
The gate at `_cve05_guard_gate()` catches the magic-256
specifically; generalize the principle.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "macho_syscall_number_dual_definition_61_vs_217"
description = "SYS_GETDENTS64 is defined as 217 (x86/macos) AND 61 (aarch64-Linux) in different stdlib files; the wrapper binds 61 by include order, and the macho ESYSXLAT translated only 217→344, missing 61→344 — so arm64-macOS dir-walk silently EBADF'd. 'Works in a probe, fails in the wrapper' = a duplicate global bound differently by include order, NOT codegen."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["macho", "aarch64", "esysxlat", "syscall", "getdirentries", "include-order", "v6.0.63"]
content = """
**The trap**: `cyrius lib sync` (and any dir-walk — is_dir,
dir_list) returned EBADF on arm64 macOS and reported "snapshot
lib not found" on a directory that demonstrably exists. The .60
fix had already added a macho ESYSXLAT entry translating x86
getdents64 217 → Darwin getdirentries 344, and a standalone
probe calling dir_list WORKED — so it looked fixed and was
mis-filed as an "arm64 arg-corruption codegen bug."

**Why the probe lied**: `SYS_GETDENTS64` is defined in MULTIPLE
files with DIFFERENT values:
  lib/fs.cyr                    : var SYS_GETDENTS64 = 217;  (x86)
  lib/syscalls_macos.cyr        : 217
  lib/syscalls_aarch64_linux.cyr: 61   (the aarch64 number)
cyrius is "last definition wins". The wrapper (cbt/cyrius.cyr)
includes fs.cyr (217) THEN syscalls.cyr (→ aarch64 → 61), so it
binds **61**. A small probe with a different include order bound
217. Same source line, opposite value.

**Why 61 failed**: the macho ESYSXLAT chain translated x86
217→344 but had NO 61→344 entry — even though the wrapper/tools
pull the aarch64 stdlib (61). Untranslated 61 ran with a stale
x16 → garbage syscall → EBADF (-9). Instrumenting is_dir in the
wrapper showed `fd=3` (open OK) but `var sg = SYS_GETDENTS64`
loaded **61**, not 217.

**Fix** (src/backend/aarch64/emit.cyr, `_TARGET_MACHO==2`
ESYSXLAT block): add `cmp x8,#61; b.ne; movz x16,#344`
(0xF100F51F / 0x54000041 / 0xD2802B10, llvm-mc-verified) beside
the 217→344 entry. Both numbers now translate, robust to
include order.

**Recognize it again**: "works in a minimal probe, fails in the
wrapper/tools" → DON'T reach for a codegen hypothesis. Print the
actual VALUE of any global the failing path reads
(`var x = THE_GLOBAL;` + write it). A duplicate global bound
differently by include order is far more likely than
context-sensitive codegen. The WRAPPER (full include set), not a
probe, is the real test. See retros/v60x.cyml + the .63 CHANGELOG.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "macho_output_basename_breaks_reproducible_cmp"
description = "Mach-O embeds the output binary's basename (the ad-hoc code-signature identifier), so compiling the same source to two DIFFERENT names (fib vs fib2) yields binaries that differ by exactly the name bytes — a false 'non-reproducible'. ELF doesn't embed the name, so Linux passes and hides it. Corollary: never codesign-compare; codesign is non-deterministic."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["macho", "reproducibility", "codesign", "v6.0.63", "v6.0.44"]
content = """
**The trap**: a reproducible-build check compiled the same
source twice — to `build/fib` and `build/fib2` — then compared
hashes. They differed on macOS but matched on Linux. It looked
like macOS compiler non-determinism.

**Root cause**: the Mach-O embeds the OUTPUT BASENAME (it's the
ad-hoc code-signature identifier / a build id). Two different
output names → the binaries differ by exactly those name bytes.
`cmp -l` showed a SINGLE differing byte, at the offset of the
embedded name (`1` vs `2` in the "…fib1"/"…fib2" string). ELF
does NOT embed the output name, so the same check passed on
Linux and hid the issue for the whole platform.

**Confirm in 30s**: build the same source to the SAME output
name twice → byte-identical. Build to different names → differ
by the name. The compiler is deterministic; the test was wrong.

**Two rules for any Mach-O reproducibility / self-host check**:
1. Rebuild to the SAME output name, never name1/name2.
2. Hash/compare the UNSIGNED output, never the codesigned
   artifact — `codesign` is non-deterministic (the v6.0.44
   lesson: a codesign-compare produced a false "non-reproducible"
   retraction). To RUN a Mach-O on macOS you MUST codesign it
   (AMFI), so `cp` the unsigned bytes aside BEFORE signing and
   compare those. This bit the .63 functional gate AND the macho
   self-host check in the same session (a signed r1 vs unsigned
   r2 differs by ~20 KB of signature).
"""

[[entries]]
name = "aarch64_atomic_on_global_needs_8_aligned_var_base"
description = "aarch64 ldxr/stxr (what atomic_cas/atomic_fetch_add compile to) MANDATORILY fault with SIGBUS on a non-8-aligned address, even where plain access is permitted. cyrius globals were only 4-byte aligned because the aarch64 ELF var-area base inherited the 4-alignment of the code size — so atomic_cas on a GLOBAL SIGBUS'd. x86 already rounds code to 8; aarch64 rounded to 4. Fix: round code size to 8 in src/backend/aarch64/fixup.cyr."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["aarch64", "atomic", "alignment", "ldxr", "sigbus", "fixup", "var-base", "v6.0.64"]
content = """
**The trap**: `atomic_cas(&someGlobal, ...)` SIGBUSes on
aarch64 (exit 135), while the SAME call on a heap pointer
(alloc returns 8-aligned) or a stack local works fine. The
v6.0.64 thread-safe allocator's `var _alloc_lock = 0;` was
the FIRST-ever atomic op on a global, so it was the first to
trip this — every prior `atomic_cas` user (thread.cyr mutex,
atomics.tcyr) used heap/stack cells.

**Why**: aarch64 `ldxr`/`stxr` (load/store-EXCLUSIVE — what
`atomic_cas` / `atomic_fetch_add` in lib/atomic.cyr compile
to) require natural (8-byte) alignment of the address and
fault on a misaligned one EVEN when SCTLR.A=0 lets ordinary
loads be unaligned. Exclusive accesses are special-cased by
the architecture; there is no unaligned `ldxr`.

**Root cause (the layout, NOT atomic.cyr)**: cyrius globals
live in the ELF var area whose RUNTIME base is
`0x400000 + 120 + cp` (`EMITELF`) / `entry + preamble + acp`
(the fixup `dbase`), where `cp` = code size. aarch64
instructions are 4 bytes, so `cp` is only 4-aligned; when
`cp ≡ 4 (mod 8)` the whole var area is 4-aligned and EVERY
global lands at a 4-aligned address. x86's fixup rounds code
to 8 (`cp = (cp+7)&~7`) precisely so its data base is
8-aligned; aarch64's fixup rounded to 4 (`(cp+3)&~4`).

**The tell**: `&g mod 8 == 4` on aarch64 but `== 0` on x86
for the SAME source. The layout is NOT arch-shared — the
byte OFFSET of a global is identical (shared frontend) but
the BASE alignment differs between backends.

**Fix** (v6.0.64, one line, `src/backend/aarch64/fixup.cyr`):
change the post-emit `cp = (cp + 3) & (0 - 4); SCP(S, cp);`
to `(cp + 7) & (0 - 8)`. `SCP` stores it, so `EMITELF`,
`EMITELF_KERNEL`, `EMITMACHO_ARM64`, and the `dbase` global
fixups all read one consistent size via `GCP` — no
inconsistency between where a global is addressed and where
it's written. ≤4 extra zero pad bytes in `.text` (never
executed). Mach-O is unaffected (its `__DATA` is page-aligned,
independent of `cp`). This makes atomic-on-ANY-global work on
aarch64, matching x86 — not just the allocator lock.

**Recognize it again**: any new aarch64 SIGBUS (exit 135) in
a program that does an atomic on a `var`-declared global, or
a "self-host failed on pi (rc=135)" when a stale
`build/cycc_aarch64` cross-compiler emits the old 4-aligned
base. Rebuild `build/cycc_aarch64` after the fixup change.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "aarch64_atomic_cas_is_not_a_full_barrier"
description = "lib/atomic.cyr's atomic_cas is documented as 'a full barrier on both arches' — TRUE on x86 (lock cmpxchg) but FALSE on aarch64, where it's plain ldxr/stxr with NO dmb. A spinlock/mutex built on it needs an EXPLICIT post-CAS atomic_fence() for the acquire barrier (thread.cyr mutex_lock has it; the v6.0.64 alloc lock initially forgot it)."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["aarch64", "atomic", "memory-ordering", "acquire-barrier", "spinlock", "weak-memory", "v6.0.64"]
content = """
**The trap**: building a lock as `while (atomic_cas(m,0,1)==0){}`
and assuming the CAS gives you the acquire barrier. It does on
x86 (`lock cmpxchg` is a full barrier) but NOT on aarch64:
lib/atomic.cyr's aarch64 `atomic_cas` is plain `ldxr`/`stxr`
with NO `dmb ish` (not the `ldaxr`/`stlxr` acquire/release
forms). So critical-section loads (e.g. `_heap_ptr`) can be
observed BEFORE the lock is actually held → stale read →
corruption that only manifests under real contention on a weak
memory model (invisible on x86, invisible single-threaded).

**The canonical pattern** (lib/thread.cyr `mutex_lock`):
spin-CAS to acquire, THEN `atomic_fence()` — the comment there
notes the fence is "a cheap no-op on x86" (cmpxchg already a
barrier) but REQUIRED on aarch64. Release mirrors `mutex_unlock`:
`atomic_fence(); atomic_store(m, 0);`.

**What bit us** (v6.0.64): `_alloc_lock_acquire` trusted
atomic.cyr's "full barrier on both arches" comment and omitted
the post-CAS fence. The release side was correct (it copied
mutex_unlock). Adversarial review caught the missing acquire
fence before ship; a 4-thread contended run on real aarch64
(pi) validated the fix. atomic.cyr's "full barrier" doc is
aspirational for aarch64 — treat `atomic_cas`/`atomic_fetch_add`
as ATOMIC but UNORDERED there, and fence explicitly.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "portable_sleep_no_raw_nanosleep_off_linux"
description = "Raw syscall(35) nanosleep faults off Linux: Darwin has NO plain nanosleep BSD syscall (and on aarch64 macho, 35 COLLIDES with unlinkat), and PE never routed 35. Portable sleep = poll(NULL,0,ms) on Linux+macOS (poll 7→230 is routed on both Mach-O backends) + a kernel32 Sleep reroute on Windows. WaitForSingleObject on a process/thread pseudo-handle does NOT block as a sleep."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["macho", "windows", "syscall", "nanosleep", "poll", "sleep", "esysxlat", "v6.0.65"]
content = """
**The trap**: `syscall(35, &timespec, 0)` (Linux nanosleep) in a
stdlib/consumer sleep helper works on Linux and faults or
misbehaves on every other target:
- **macOS**: XNU has no plain `nanosleep` BSD syscall (libsystem
  builds it over semaphore primitives). Worse, on aarch64-macho
  the number 35 COLLIDES — ESYSXLAT maps aarch64 `35` to
  `unlinkat`→`unlink`, so `syscall(35, ts, 0)` tries to unlink a
  garbage path. (The x86-nanosleep-35 vs aarch64-unlinkat-35
  clash is the same multiply-defined-number swamp as the .63
  getdents 61-vs-217 bug.)
- **Windows (PE)**: 35 is not a routed reroute → fault.

**The portable fix** (v6.0.65, `lib/chrono.cyr` `sleep_ms`):
- Linux + macOS: `poll(NULL, 0, ms)` — `poll` (x86 7 → Darwin 230)
  is ALREADY routed on both Mach-O backends (the .59 socket port),
  and `poll` with 0 fds + a timeout is the portable ms-granular
  sleep. Verified ≈ms-accurate on Linux + ecb + ach (the constant
  ~300ms "overhead" the first time on macOS is one-shot
  codesign/AMFI launch, not poll — baseline-subtract to confirm).
- Windows: a real kernel32 `Sleep(ms)` reroute (0xF00F), 1-arg,
  mirroring the SRWLock reroutes.
- agnos/cx: no-op (no sleep syscall / single-threaded VM).

**Windows dead-end worth knowing**: `WaitForSingleObject(handle,
ms)` on the current-PROCESS (-1) or current-THREAD (-2)
pseudo-handle returns IMMEDIATELY — it does NOT block for the
timeout (verified on cass: 0 ms). It only blocks on a genuinely
non-signaled object. So there's no "sleep via the already-routed
WaitForSingleObject" shortcut; you need a real `Sleep` reroute.

**Measurement gotcha (cmd.exe)**: `cmd /c "echo %TIME% & prog &
echo %TIME%"` prints the SAME time twice — `%TIME%` expands at
parse time (once), the `%errorlevel%` gotcha applied to TIME. Use
`cmd /v:on /c "... !TIME! ..."` or PowerShell `Measure-Command`.

**Recognize again**: any consumer doing raw `syscall(35)` for a
sleep on macOS/Windows; or a new "syscall not routed on Mach-O"
warning naming 35. The fix is always: route through
`lib/chrono.cyr sleep_ms`, never hardcode nanosleep.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "cyrius_test_apple_silicon_qemu_and_codesign"
description = "cyrius test/run/bench/fuzz/doctest failed on arm64 macOS via two stacked cbt bugs: (1) run_binary took the qemu-aarch64 cross-run branch on a NATIVE Apple-Silicon host (find_tools forces _arch=AARCH64) → no qemu → execve-fail → exit 127; (2) the compiled /tmp binary ran UNsigned → AMFI SIGKILL → exit 137. A compile-and-run command on macho must exec natively (never qemu) AND ad-hoc codesign first."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["cbt", "macho", "apple-silicon", "codesign", "qemu", "run_binary", "cyrius-test", "v6.0.66"]
content = """
**The trap**: `cyrius test` (and run/bench/fuzz/doctest) fail on
arm64 macOS with a bare **exit 127** and zero test output — only on
the macOS runner, unchanged by any compiler fix. Two cbt bugs stack:

**Bug 1 (the 127) — qemu mis-route.** `cbt/build.cyr run_binary`
had an `if (_arch == ARCH_AARCH64) { exec /usr/bin/qemu-aarch64 }`
branch — the x86-Linux-host path for cross-running aarch64 test
binaries under qemu-user. But `find_tools()` (cbt/core.cyr) forces
`_arch=AARCH64` on arm64-macOS so current_cc picks the native macho
cycc — which made run_binary ALSO take the qemu branch on a NATIVE
Apple-Silicon host, where there is no `/usr/bin/qemu-aarch64` →
execve fails → `sys_exit(127)`. The binary never runs (zero output;
the literal 127). Fix (v6.0.66): gate the qemu branch
`#ifndef CYRIUS_TARGET_MACOS` — a native Mach-O host execs directly.

**Bug 2 (the next domino, 137) — unsigned AMFI SIGKILL.** Even with
Bug 1 fixed, the freshly-compiled `/tmp/cyrius_test_bin` is UNsigned,
and arm64 macOS AMFI SIGKILLs unsigned binaries (128+9=137). Only
`cmd_build` ad-hoc-codesigned (v6.0.38); test/run/bench/fuzz/doctest
compiled to /tmp and ran via run_binary without signing. Fix: hoist
the codesign into a shared `_macho_codesign()` and call it INSIDE
run_binary so every run path signs (cmd_build DRY'd to it). No-op off
macOS; harmless on x86-macOS (codesign -s - rejects but unsigned runs
there anyway).

**Why it masked on ecb but not the hosted runner**: ecb (the dev
Apple-Silicon box) had qemu-user installed, and qemu happily runs a
native-arch binary too (AMFI-bypassed) — so run_binary's qemu branch
"worked" there. The hosted macos-15-arm64 runner has neither qemu nor
(post-fix-1) a signature → it exposes both bugs. Classic ecb-vs-runner
split: "run it on the ACTUAL CI target, not just the dev box."

**Recognize again**: any cbt compile-and-run command exiting 127
(qemu/exec-fail, zero output) or 137 (AMFI SIGKILL) on Apple Silicon.
The rule: on macho, exec natively (never qemu) and `_macho_codesign`
the binary before exec.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "callptr_indirect_call_frame_slot_spill_survives_win64_shadow"
description = "v6.0.70: compiler-emitted indirect calls (callptr → IR_CALL_INDIRECT, x86 `call [rbp-disp]` / aarch64 `ldr x6;blr x6`). The crux is callee-survival across ECALLPOPS: the obvious 'push callee, pop after ECALLPOPS' is WRONG on Win64 (ECALLPOPS does `sub rsp,0x20` for the shadow home → buries a stack-pushed callee) and on SysV n>6. The correct general fix is to spill the callee to a FRESH frame local before the args (rbp-relative → unaffected by ECALLPOPS's rsp moves, re-entrant for nested callptr, any arg count). aarch64 must load into x6 (x0-x5 are arg regs, x9 is the >6-arg shuffle scratch). Open caveat: a real Win64 COM callee still corrupts the caller frame (callptr to a trivial callee works) — .71."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["callptr", "indirect-call", "ir_call_indirect", "com", "vtable", "win64", "shadow-space", "frame-slot", "ffi", "v6.0.70"]
content = """
**Compiler-emitted indirect call (callptr/IR_CALL_INDIRECT) — the
callee-survival problem is the whole game.** To call through a computed
pointer (a COM vtable method, a fn-ptr value), the callee value must be
LIVE in a register at the `call`/`blr` — but it has to survive (a) the
arg evaluation (which uses the rax/x0 accumulator) and (b) ECALLPOPS
(which marshals the pushed args into arg regs and, on Win64, `sub rsp,0x20`
for the shadow home).

**The wrong design (the understand-workflow proposed it, it's WRONG for
Win64):** push the callee FIRST (deepest), push args, ECALLPOPS, then POP
the callee into rax and `call rax`. This only works on SysV n<=6. On Win64,
ECALLPOPS does `sub rsp,0x20` AFTER draining the args, so the callee
(pushed before the args) is now BURIED 0x20 below rsp — popping gets the
shadow, not the callee. SysV n>6 also shuffles/drops slots. Verify against
ECALLPOPS (src/backend/x86/emit.cyr) before trusting any callee-survival
scheme — the shadow `sub rsp` is the trap.

**The right design (frame-slot spill):** in the callptr parser arm,
allocate a FRESH frame local (`GFLC` → `EFLSTORE` → `SFLC+1`), spill the
evaluated callee there BEFORE pushing args, then after ECALLPOPS emit
ECALLIND = `call [rbp-disp]` (x86, FF /2 mod=10 rm=101) / `ldr x6,[x29-disp]
; blr x6` (aarch64). rbp/x29-relative → immune to ECALLPOPS's rsp moves;
re-entrant (nested callptr → distinct slots, since each grabs the next GFLC
slot); works for any arg count + ABI. The frame auto-grows (EPATCHFRAME
sizes from GFLC at fn-end). IR_CALL_INDIRECT carries the spill idx (arg1);
its DCE predicates: clobbers_rax (return), def_rcx_any (caller-save),
uses_rax conservatively (matches the call cohort).

**aarch64 register: x6, not x0.** ECALLPOPS loads arg0 into x0 and uses x9
as the >6-arg memory shuffle. x6 is outside the 6 arg regs (x0-x5) and
isn't x9 → it survives ECALLPOPS for any argc. (lib/fnptr.cyr's asm uses
x9, but that's the boilerplate being replaced — don't copy x9.)

**callptr needs a function frame.** The spill is a frame local, so callptr
at TOP LEVEL is a loud compile error (top-level vars are globals → no rbp
frame; `_cur_fn_ix < 0` detects it). cx has no indirect-call bytecode op →
loud error there too. Both fail loud, never silent-wrong.

**Open gotcha (v6.0.71):** callptr to a TRIVIAL cyrius callee works on all
4 hosts (incl. Win64, loaded-callee 2/3-arg). But callptr to a REAL Win64
COM callee (a DXGI vtable method) corrupts the cyrius caller frame on cass
(RC=5 / access-violation) even when the COM call returns S_OK — NOT a slot
error (slot 7 and 12 both fail) and NOT the primitive (verified). A subtle
real-Win64-callee interaction; needs windbg on cass to pin. See
issues/2026-06-05-windows-com-vtable-real-callee-frame-corruption.md.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "pe_multi_dll_imports_byte_identical_refactor_and_cross_arch_stubs"
description = "v6.0.69: generalized the PE backend from ONE hardcoded kernel32 import descriptor to N DLLs (shell32, then dxgi). Three reusable lessons: (1) the flat ftype=4 IAT fixup assumed imp_idx==IAT-slot, so grouping imports by DLL into per-descriptor null-terminated IAT/ILT runs forced an imp_idx→physical-slot remap (_pe_iat_slot); (2) design the generalization to be BYTE-IDENTICAL at one DLL so it's a provable no-op before adding the 2nd; (3) PE-reroute emit fns live in x86/emit.cyr but parse_expr.cyr calls them inside a runtime `if (_TARGET_PE==1)` block that compiles on EVERY backend → aarch64/emit.cyr needs no-op stubs or it's FATAL under --strict."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["pe", "windows", "imports", "iat", "ffi", "shell32", "byte-identical", "cross-arch-stub", "utf16", "v6.0.69"]
content = """
**Generalizing the PE import table from 1 DLL to N (the Windows FFI
foundation).** Pre-v6.0.69 the PE backend hardcoded a single kernel32
import descriptor: `_pe_imp_dir_size = 20*2` (one descriptor + null),
literal `"kernel32.dll"`, and a FLAT IAT/ILT where imp_idx directly
indexed the thunk slot. shell32 (CommandLineToArgvW) + dxgi
(CreateDXGIFactory1) both need a non-kernel32 descriptor.

**(1) The flat ftype=4 fixup is the constraint.** `src/backend/x86/fixup.cyr`
resolves a PE IAT call as `iat_rva = idata + iat_off + imp_idx*8` — imp_idx
IS the physical slot. But a multi-DLL IAT must group each DLL's thunks into
a contiguous, per-descriptor null-terminated run (the loader walks each
descriptor's ILT to a null and fills the matching IAT run). Grouping breaks
imp_idx==slot. Fix: tag each import with a DLL id (`_pe_imp_dll`), in
`_pe_layout` walk DLL ids ascending (kernel32=0 FIRST so ExitProcess stays
at slot 0), assign physical slots per group with a null after each, and
record `_pe_iat_pos[imp_idx]` → consumed by the fixup via `_pe_iat_slot(idx)`.
The fixup FORMAT is unchanged (still a flat imp_idx); only the resolution
gains a lookup.

**(2) Byte-identical-at-N=1 is the safety proof.** Design every size/offset
so one DLL reproduces the old layout exactly: `(dll_count+1)*20` == `20*2`,
grouped order == imp_idx order, `_pe_iat_pos[i]==i`, one trailing null. Then
VERIFY before adding DLL #2: compile the same Windows program with the old
and new compiler → identical bytes (got an identical 2560-byte PE). A PE-
layout refactor that's a proven no-op at N=1 can't have regressed the 25
existing kernel32 imports; only the genuinely-new 2nd-DLL path is untested,
and the cass run covers that. This pattern (prove the generalization is
inert on the existing case, THEN extend) beats trying to eyeball RVA math.

**(3) Cross-arch stubs for x86-only emit fns.** The PE-reroute emitters
(`ECMDTOARGV_PE`, `ELOCALFREE_PE`, `ESLEEP_PE`, …) live in
`src/backend/x86/emit.cyr`. `src/frontend/parse_expr.cyr` calls them inside
a RUNTIME `if (_TARGET_PE == 1)` block (not `#ifdef`), so that code COMPILES
on the aarch64/macho/cx backends too — where the symbols don't exist. Each
needs a `fn EXXX_PE(S) { return 0; }` no-op stub in
`src/backend/aarch64/emit.cyr` (the dead `_TARGET_PE` branch never runs
there). WITHOUT the stub it's a warning on a normal build but **FATAL under
--strict** — and cross-os pi surfaces the `undefined function` warning
loud. When you add ANY new PE-reroute fn, add its aarch64 stub in the SAME
slot (cross-arch-propagation-mandatory). cx has no stubs and tolerates the
warning (mirrors ESLEEP_PE) — match whatever the existing cohort does.

**Bonus — Windows argv is UTF-16.** GetCommandLineW / CommandLineToArgvW
return UTF-16LE. The v6.0.54 tokenizer down-converted ASCII-only (drop the
high byte) → non-ASCII paths corrupted silently. `_args_w2u8` (lib/args.cyr,
host-testable) does real UTF-16→UTF-8 incl. surrogate-pair decode (high
0xD800-0xDBFF + low 0xDC00-0xDFFF → one U+10000+ code point → 4-byte UTF-8).
"""

[[entries]]
name = "aarch64_linux_esysxlat_gaps_native_divergence_placebo_gate"
description = "v6.0.68: the aarch64-Linux ESYSXLAT (src/backend/aarch64/emit.cyr, non-macho branch) was missing x86→aarch64 translations for literal syscalls cbt issues — stat 4 (ran as io_getevents → _file_size=-1 → `cyrius deps` include-scan short-circuited → transitive stdlib silently dropped = §D1), rename 82 (=fsync → `cyrius build` never renamed its .tmp output), symlink 88 (pulsar). PLUS: main_aarch64_native.cyr (the SHIPPED native cycc) silently diverged from main_aarch64.cyr — never got the v5.9.37 auto-call-main port → bare `fn main()` builds exited 0. PLUS: the CI gate tested the cross binary, not the shipped native one (placebo)."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["aarch64", "esysxlat", "syscall", "deps", "rename", "symlink", "stat", "auto-call-main", "native-vs-cross", "placebo-gate", "found-by-ports", "v6.0.68"]
content = """
**Three bugs, one goal (make the aarch64-native funcgate HARD), all in
the aarch64-Linux NATIVE toolchain. Found because §D1's deps fix let the
soft funcgate finally reach its later steps — a classic mask-chain.**

**(1) ESYSXLAT is x86-numbered everywhere; a literal `syscall(N)` in cbt
needs an aarch64 translation or it hits the WRONG aarch64 syscall.**
The aarch64 backend translates x86 syscall numbers → aarch64 via the
ESYSXLAT cmp/b.ne/movz chain (`src/backend/aarch64/emit.cyr`, non-macho
branch, after the `_TARGET_MACHO==2` return). It was INCOMPLETE relative
to the macho branch. `cbt` issues several syscalls as bare literals:
- `stat 4`  → aarch64 4 is `io_getevents`. `_file_size` (cbt/deps.cyr)
  → -1 → the deps transitive-include scan does `if (sz<=0) return 0`
  → peers (`syscalls_aarch64_linux.cyr`, `alloc_*`, `atomic`) silently
  dropped. THIS is §D1 ("cyrius deps silently fails on aarch64").
- `rename 82` → aarch64 82 is `fsync`. `cyrius build` builds to
  `out.tmp.<pid>` then renames; rename no-op'd → the final binary never
  appeared (rc=0, no output, no error).
- `symlink 88` → aarch64 has no symlink(2). `cyrius pulsar` install
  symlinks failed.
Fix: add `stat 4→fstatat 79`, `rename 82→renameat 38`, `symlink
88→symlinkat 36`, each with the AT_FDCWD arg-shift (mirror the existing
`openat 2→56` reroute). **Ordering gotcha:** put `stat 4→79` AFTER
`getcwd 79→17`, else the `x8=79` it sets is re-caught by `cmp x8,#79`
and double-translated to getcwd. (`fcntl 72` is macho-only F_GETPATH;
aarch64-Linux uses the getcwd `#else` path, so it needs no entry.)
Assembler-verify every hand-rolled encoding (`as` + `objdump -d` on the
target, `cmp` the bytes) — the renameat/symlinkat arg-shifts are easy to
get subtly wrong.

**(2) main_aarch64_native.cyr can silently diverge from
main_aarch64.cyr.** There are TWO aarch64 entry files — the CROSS
(`main_aarch64.cyr`, x86-host) and the NATIVE (`main_aarch64_native.cyr`,
aarch64-host → the SHIPPED `build/cycc-native-aarch64`). They share the
backend but each carries its OWN copy of the entry/epilogue logic,
including the v5.9.37 auto-call-`main` trampoline (walks the fn table for
"main\\0", emits ECALLTO). The cross had it; macho got it v6.0.37, win
v6.0.54 — the NATIVE never did. So `cycc-native-aarch64` never invoked a
bare `fn main()` → every such `cyrius build` on real ARM exited with junk
(0). It still SELF-HOSTS byte-identical because the compiler's own source
`sys_exit`s explicitly (no bare `fn main`). **When you port an
entry-level emit fix, grep ALL `main_*.cyr` — the per-target forks rot
independently, and the bug shows on USER programs, never on self-host.**

**(3) A gate that tests the wrong binary is a placebo.** The CI
`aarch64-native` job built/self-hosted/funcgated `cycc_a64` =
`main_aarch64.cyr` piped through the cross — NOT the shipped
`main_aarch64_native.cyr` binary. So bug (2) stayed green for the gate's
whole life (the cross had auto-call-main). Same disease as the macOS-rot
incident: **the gate must build + run the artifact users INSTALL** (here:
`main_aarch64_native.cyr → cycc_native_a64`, self-hosted from its OWN
source). Test what ships, not a same-arch lookalike.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "param_load_pseudo_and_bootstrap_coupling"
description = "asm-block param_load(reg, idx) (v6.0.67) emits a param load at the prologue-correct disp = -(idx+1+_cur_fn_regalloc)*8 — byte-identical to the hand-rolled [rbp-N]/[x29,#-N] literals (disp8 mov / ldur). BUT: migrating a BOOTSTRAP-CRITICAL lib (atomic.cyr is in cycc via the .64 alloc lock) to a NEW compiler feature couples that lib to the feature — a pre-feature cycc can't compile it (the smoke gate catches a stale install)."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["asm", "param_load", "prologue", "bootstrap", "atomic", "regalloc", "v6.0.67"]
content = """
**The feature**: `param_load(reg, idx)` inside an `asm { }` block
emits a load of the idx-th parameter from its ACTUAL prologue slot,
so inline asm stops hardcoding `[rbp-N]` / `[x29,#-N]` byte literals
that silently break when the prologue layout shifts (the recurring
sigil AES-NI / cyrius atomic.cyr coupling bug). Implementation
(src/backend/{x86,aarch64}/emit.cyr): match "param_load" in
ASM_MNEMONIC (first-8 L64 `0x6F6C5F6D61726170` + verify trailing
"ad"), parse `(reg, idx)`, map reg name → number
(`_asm_{x86,aarch64}_reg`), emit at disp = -(idx+1+_cur_fn_regalloc)*8.
x86 → `48 8B (0x45|rl<<3) disp8` (mod=01, rm=rbp); aarch64 →
`0xF8400000 | ((disp&0x1FF)<<12) | (29<<5) | reg` (ldur). Tokens:
LPAREN=10, RPAREN=11, COMMA=31 (NOT 28 — that's LBRACKET).

**Byte-identical check**: param_load with regalloc=0 emits EXACTLY
the old hand-rolled literals (`param_load(rdi,0)` → `48 8B 7D F8`;
`param_load(x0,0)` → `A0 83 5F F8`). Migrating atomic.cyr produced a
byte-identical cycc — the cleanest possible correctness proof (atomic.cyr
is compiled INTO cycc via the v6.0.64 alloc lock).

**The bootstrap-coupling gotcha (the real lesson)**: migrating a
BOOTSTRAP-CRITICAL lib to a NEW compiler feature couples that lib to
the feature. atomic.cyr/thread.cyr are in cycc's own source → after
migration they REQUIRE a param_load-capable (≥6.0.67) cycc. A stale
installed cycc (or a frozen pre-feature stage) can't compile them —
the `cyrius smoke` gate (which uses the INSTALLED cycc on a .smcyr that
includes atomic.cyr) caught exactly this with a 6.0.66 install. Safe
because: consumers get lib+cycc together via `cyrius deps`; the bootstrap
propagates param_load from the CURRENT backend (cybs does NOT compile
main.cyr directly — `cat main.cyr | cybs` fails pre-existing, so cybs is
not the main.cyr compiler); pulsar's self-host chain carries it forward.
Smoke passes once .67 is installed. **Before migrating any bootstrap-
critical lib to a new feature, weigh this coupling** — for a consumer-
only feature you can ship it WITHOUT migrating cyrius's own libs.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "macos_owns_thread_pointer_register"
description = "macOS owns TPIDR_EL0 (arm64) / %fs (x86) — Darwin saves+restores it as thread state and overwrites any userspace `msr TPIDR_EL0` / arch_prctl on the FIRST preemption, so cyrius cannot durably own the thread-pointer register for thread-local storage on macOS."
detail = """
v6.0.84. Symptom: sigil's crypto-scratch bank (`cbank()` → `thread_local_get`,
lib/thread_local.cyr) SIGSEGV'd on real ecb (Apple Silicon) AFTER an ECDSA
sign — but every ingredient (sha256, hmac, fl_alloc, the secret vars, the
rfc6979 reject loop) ran clean in isolation. The .76 issue chased it to a
`&_fl_heads` freelist codegen bug via an early lldb; THAT DIAGNOSIS WAS WRONG —
the `&global` adrp+add path is provably correct (EVADDR emits a fresh
adrp+add per site, FIXUP_ADRP_ADD masks 0x9F00001F so it can't corrupt the
opcode, var-address resolution is deterministic per index).

Real cause: thread_local.cyr installs a per-thread block via `msr TPIDR_EL0`
(arm64) and reads it back via `mrs TPIDR_EL0`. On Linux the kernel lets EL0
own TPIDR_EL0. On Darwin the kernel uses it for its own thread self-data and
RESTORES it on every context switch. Decisive repro on ecb: install the
block (TPIDR=0x1xxxxxxxx), run a 2-billion-iteration pure-compute loop with
ZERO syscalls, read TPIDR again → 0x200d (a Darwin thread value). Pure
preemption, no syscall, clobbers it. `cbank()` lazy-inits ONCE
(`_crypto_tls_inited` guard), so the first preemption during crypto poisons
every later `thread_local_get`. This is why it looked "context-dependent,
after a preceding svc" — it's preemption, and a long crypto op always gets
preempted.

How to recognize: lldb shows the fault at `ldr xN, [x1, x0, lsl #3]` right
after `mrs x1, TPIDR_EL0`, with x1 a tiny value (~0x2010), NOT a heap addr.

Fix: a macOS process-global slot array (no TPIDR), like the Windows TlsAlloc
path. Safe because cyrius threads don't run on macOS at all — thread.cyr is
clone(2)-only (no Darwin bsdthread path) — so crypto-scratch is
single-threaded. Since preemption (not a syscall) is the trigger, NO
"re-msr before access" scheme is reliable; you must not use the register.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "macho_socketpair_dual_number_199_vs_53"
description = "socketpair's syscall number differs by macho arch: arm-macho pulls syscalls_aarch64_linux.cyr → 199; x86-macho pulls syscalls_macos.cyr → 53. The ESYSXLAT must map BOTH to Darwin 135 (in their respective backends). And on the arm enum, 53 is fchmodat (already mapped) — reusing 53 there collides."
detail = """
v6.0.84 (cf. the v6.0.63 getdents64 61-vs-217 dual-number trap). There is no
syscalls_aarch64_macos.cyr: lib/syscalls.cyr routes arm-macho to
syscalls_aarch64_linux.cyr (aarch64-Linux numbers) and x86-macho to
syscalls_macos.cyr (x86 numbers). So a socket added only as the x86 number is
DEAD on arm-macho. socketpair was the last untranslated one (the .59 socket
surface added socket/connect/accept/bind/listen but not socketpair): the
fork+socketpair TLS e2e (tls12_handshake.tcyr) ran svc with a stale x16 →
garbage fds → TLS_ERR_IO on every read/write. Symptom of a totally
untranslated number on Darwin: SIGSYS (exit 140 = 128+12).

Fix: aarch64-macho ESYSXLAT `cmp x8,#199; movz x16,#135` (NOT 53 — 53 is
fchmodat on the aarch64-Linux enum, already mapped to chmod with an arg-shift,
so a 53 entry both misses real socketpair AND corrupts fchmodat). x86-macho
EMACHO_SYSXLAT `_msx(S, 53, 0x2000087)` (53 is socketpair on the x86 enum,
no collision). Keep `_macho_arm_routes` in lockstep (it whitelists the
unrouted-syscall warning). Encodings: `as -arch arm64` on ecb.

STILL LATENT (v6.0.84): the socket FAMILY (socket/connect/accept/bind/listen)
is mapped ONLY as x86 numbers (41-50) in the aarch64-macho ESYSXLAT, so
real-network sockets are likely broken on arm-macho (the .81 live-Cloudflare
proof was on Linux). The socketpair e2e doesn't need them.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "windows_install_pillar_env_spawn_exe"
description = "Making `cyrius build` work on Windows took three wrapper layers, each invisible until run on real cass: (1) no /proc env-read on Windows; (2) the wrapper looked for `cycc` not `cycc.exe` and defaulted _home=/root; (3) compile()/run_binary use POSIX fork/dup2/execve which Win32 lacks."
detail = """
v6.0.85. The cross-OS gate had cycc.exe SELF-HOSTING green for a long time, but
`cyrius` (the wrapper) could neither find nor run it on Windows - so a real
install was unusable. Each layer surfaced only by running on cass (do NOT trust
the self-host verdict for the install pillar; see the methodology notes).

1. ENV READ. cbt/core.cyr + lib/io.cyr + _read_env all read /proc/self/environ
   (Linux) or _macho_fill_environ (macOS). Windows has NEITHER, so CYRIUS_HOME /
   USERPROFILE were invisible and _home defaulted to "/root". Fix: a new PE
   reroute syscall(0xF015) -> kernel32!GetEnvironmentVariableA (3 args:
   name->rcx, buf->rdx, size->r8; needs a 3-arg 16-byte-aligned caller
   _pe_call_3arg_aligned). Register the import in pe/emit.cyr
   (_pe_register_kernel32), emit in x86/emit.cyr, dispatch in parse_expr.cyr,
   aarch64 no-op stub (FATAL under --strict otherwise).

2. .EXE SUFFIX. current_cc() (cbt/core.cyr) resolved <home>/bin/cycc. Windows
   binaries are cycc.exe - guard the name with #ifdef CYRIUS_TARGET_WIN.

3. SPAWN. compile() (cbt/build.cyr) and run_binary() invoke cycc via sys_fork +
   sys_dup2 + sys_execve - all POSIX, absent on Win32. Also SYS_RENAME(82) and
   getpid(39) are NOT PE reroutes, so the atomic tmp+rename block can't run on
   Windows. Fix: a #ifdef CYRIUS_TARGET_WIN branch that spawns
   `cycc < source > output` via cmd.exe + CreateProcessW (lib/process_win.cyr
   _win_compile_spawn), writing directly to `output`. cmd does the redirect.
   The quoting that works: `cmd /s /c "<inner>"` - /s strips ONLY the outermost
   quote pair, so per-path quotes + the < > operators reach cycc intact:
   cmd /s /c ""C:\...\cycc.exe" < "src.cyr" > "out.exe""

4. .ps1 ASCII. Windows PowerShell 5.1 reads scripts as the system ANSI
   codepage, so a UTF-8 em-dash (or any multi-byte char) breaks the parser
   ("Unexpected token"). Keep install.ps1 / cass-install-gate.ps1 ASCII-only.

5. deps --lock hash: no /bin/sh or sha256sum on Windows; use
   `certutil -hashfile <p> SHA256` and parse line 2 (the 64-hex digest;
   certutil prints a header line first, \r\n endings). cbt/deps.cyr.

The install pillar is gated by scripts/cass-install-gate.{sh,ps1} (cyrius audit):
real install.ps1 -> cyrius build fn main(){return 42} -> assert exit 42 - the
Windows analog of the ecb install gate. The release tarball (build-windows-
tarball.sh, single source of truth) now ships cyrius.exe + install.ps1; it
previously shipped neither, so even a "successful" download had no wrapper.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "callptr_callee_spill_aliases_addr_taken_local"
description = "The callptr indirect-call callee-spill frame slot (v6.0.70) can ALIAS a `&`-taken local. When a function passes `&local` as a COM/FFI out-param and the callptr spills its callee to a GFLC frame slot, the two can land on the SAME rbp offset → the out-param write and the spilled callee fight → frame/regalloc corruption → AV on the NEXT indirect dispatch."
detail = """
v6.0.86. Symptom: lib/dxgi.cyr dxgi_vram_bytes() AV'd (0xC0000005) on real DXGI
hardware (cass) — factory + EnumAdapters1 worked, then the GetDesc1 dispatch
crashed. Looked GPU-specific + windbg-needed; it was neither.

cdb on cass (C:\\dbg\\cdb.exe — the debugger was present; a Program-Files-only +
minimal-ssh-PATH `where` search wrongly reported it absent) gave the fault:
  mov eax,0x50 ; pop rcx ; add rax,rcx ; mov rax,[rax]   with rcx(avtbl)=0
i.e. load64(avtbl + 10*8) [GetDesc1] with avtbl=0. avtbl = load64(pAdapter);
pAdapter pointed at zeroed mem. llvm-objdump of the PE showed the smoking gun:
  0x1843  mov [rbp-0x50], rax    ; EnumAdapters1 callptr callee-spill (cp_idx)
  0x1855  lea rax, [rbp-0x50]    ; &pAdapter (EnumAdapters1's out-param)
SAME slot. The v6.0.70 callptr spills the callee to `cp_idx = GFLC` and calls
`[rbp+disp(cp_idx)]`; here GFLC handed it the slot a `&`-taken local already
owned. The collision corrupted the frame/regalloc enough that a later
regalloc'd var (avtbl in r12) read stale 0.

Why it hid: frame-LAYOUT-dependent (which callptr collides shifts as you add/
remove locals — adding one local moved the AV from GetDesc1 to EnumAdapters1);
real-Win64-callee-only (a cyrius callee writes near rbp, a system DLL writes
near rsp + uses the out-param pointer hard); and INVISIBLE to self-host because
cycc has no callptr (callptr is a consumer/FFI feature) — so the bug shipped
green through every self-host gate. The v6.0.71 ECALLPTR_PE force-16-align was a
SEPARATE, real fix (SSE-spill alignment), not this.

Fix: on PE, don't spill the callee to a frame slot at all — push it on the
STACK (parser pushes it FIRST, below the args), then in ECALLPTR_PE pop the args
into rcx/rdx/r8/r9, `pop rax` (the callee, now on top), align + 32B shadow,
`call rax`. No frame slot → nothing can alias it. The non-PE path keeps the
frame-slot spill + ECALLIND (its ECALLPOPS shadow would bury a stack callee) —
unchanged, byte-identical. Verified: dxgi_vram_bytes()=128MB on cass UHD 600 +
callptr_real_win64 kernel32 regression=42 + 4-host self-host byte-identical.

Lesson echo: don't take a "needs a debugger we don't have / needs special
hardware" verdict as gospel — the debugger was on the box and the integrated GPU
reproduced it fine. See methodology / the hardware-directly field note.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "getenv_on_agnos_and_local_kernel_testability"
description = "getenv() on agnos walks the exec-stack envp from _agnos_init_rsp (agnos has no /proc); and the agnos kernel is locally testable under QEMU — rebuild + boot it and run a ring-3 cyrius binary, don't claim 'no agnos to test on'."
detail = """
v6.0.87. Two linked notes.

(1) getenv() on agnos. agnos has no /proc/self/environ (the Linux source). The
agnos kernel (1.43.2) stages a default envp (HOME=/, PWD=/) on the SysV exec
init stack. cyrius getenv() delegates under CYRIUS_TARGET_AGNOS to _agnos_getenv
in lib/args_agnos.cyr, which reads the envp from the entry init-rsp captured at
startup (the same _agnos_init_rsp that argc/argv use):
    envp[j] = load64(_agnos_init_rsp + 8 + (argc+1+j)*8)   # NUL-terminated
and matches "KEY=". The delegation lives in args_agnos.cyr (not io.cyr) because
io precedes args in the stdlib include order, so io.cyr calling _agnos_getenv is
a forward FUNCTION ref (REGFN resolves it) — a forward GLOBAL ref to
_agnos_init_rsp from io.cyr would not resolve. Every agnos program already links
args_agnos (the cycc entry emits `call _agnos_capture_rsp` for _TARGET_AGNOS), so
the global is always present.

(2) The agnos kernel is LOCALLY TESTABLE — do not claim "no agnos to run on."
   - rebuild current:  cd agnos && sh scripts/build.sh   (-> build/agnos, 1.43.2)
   - boot + run a ring-3 program under QEMU: agnos/scripts/agnsh-smoke.sh boots a
     production kernel with an ext2 rootfs whose /bin/agnsh it execs in ring 3;
     AGNSH_BIN=<your.agnos> overrides that program. exec-smoke.sh is the
     EXEC_SELFTEST disk-exec path. Both capture the serial output.
   - I verified cyrius getenv on the real kernel this way: built a probe
     (cyrius build --agnos) that prints getenv("HOME"/"PWD"/"NOPE"), ran it as
     AGNSH_BIN -> serial showed HOME=/ PWD=/ NOPE=(null). Requires
     qemu-system-x86_64 + OVMF + gnoboot built at ../gnoboot/build/.
   The kernel needs to be CURRENT (rebuild from source) — an older build/agnos
   predates the 1.43.2 envp staging and getenv would read an empty envp.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "x86_macho_byte_array_literal_self_host_invisible"
description = "The x86-macOS (Mach-O) cycc cannot compile byte-array literals (`var foo[N] = { ... };`) — a parser miscompile that is INVISIBLE to self-host because cycc's own source uses no byte-array literals, so the PARSE_GVAR_ARR path is never exercised when cycc compiles itself. The target self-hosts byte-identical while carrying a latent miscompile of a path it never runs on itself."
detail = """
v6.0.88 (surfaced by the cross-OS lib-test on ach when byte_array_literal.tcyr was
the glob). On ach the native Mach-O cycc aborts compiling the test with
`error:2358: expected ';', got '='` (line is inside the prepended stdlib includes,
not the test's byte-array lines → general parse-state corruption, x86-Mach-O only).
A trivial `syscall(60,42)` compiles+runs fine, so Mach-O execution is healthy — the
break is at parse/compile time on this build.

WHY SELF-HOST NEVER CAUGHT IT: cycc has zero `var x[N] = {...}` literals, so
PARSE_GVAR_ARR is dead during cycc's own compile. The x86-Mach-O cycc self-hosts
byte-identical (green every slot) yet miscompiles a parser path it never self-uses.
Exact "green checkmark over untested codegen" class — cf. the macOS-rot incident
(macho_syscall_number_dual_definition…) and feedback_macos_windows_ci_gate_mandatory.

VERIFY-IT-IS-PRE-EXISTING TRICK: stash the working tree to the released tag's source
on the target and rebuild the native cycc there — the released .87 fails identically,
proving a given slot's emit-layer change didn't cause a *parse* error (a codegen
change cannot). Gated behind the x86-macOS-self-compile HELD decision (Intel/EOL);
filed issues/2026-06-07-x86-macho-byte-array-literal-no-compile.md.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "byte_array_peephole_obj_aware_evrcx_not_evaddr_x1"
description = "When hoisting `&var` once for the byte-array-literal peephole, use the OBJ-AWARE base loader (_EVRCX: rip-relative LEA when _IS_OBJ, else absolute mov), NOT EVADDR_X1 (absolute-mov only). EVADDR_X1 would silently regress byte arrays compiled to relocatable objects (`-c`) / PIE on x86. aarch64/cx alias _EVRCX to their already-correct EVADDR_X1 (aarch64's has the Mach-O adrp/add branch)."
detail = """
v6.0.88. The peephole replaces the ~7-op per-byte EVADDR/EADDRA_IMM/PUSH/MOVI/POPC/
STORE8/XORAA chain with: hoist base into rcx/x1/r1 ONCE + one direct store per byte
(x86 `mov byte [rcx+disp],imm8` C6/0 disp8|disp32; aarch64 `strb w0,[x1,#imm12]`
with a >=4096 legacy fallback; cx `store8 [r1(+disp)],r0`). ~5x emit compression +
one fixup per array.

THE TRAP: the obvious "load &var into rcx" primitive EVADDR_X1 emits `mov rcx,imm64`
unconditionally — fine for a non-PIE executable, WRONG for an object/PIE target that
needs rip-relative + a relocation. The old per-byte code used EVADDR (rax) which HAS
the _IS_OBJ rip-relative branch; the naive peephole port to EVADDR_X1 drops it.
_EVRCX is the rcx-twin of EVADDR's obj-aware logic — already present in x86 emit.cyr,
used by struct-global field stores. cycc has no byte arrays → self-host byte-identical
regardless; the bug only shows in obj-mode CONSUMER codegen.

IR mode (CYRIUS_IR=1|2, opt-in) keeps the legacy IR-aware per-byte sequence so the
IR stream is unchanged; the peephole is the IR-off (default / every real build) path.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "emit_fmt_macho_before_pe_precedence"
description = "When deriving an output-format selector (`_emit_fmt`) from the _TARGET_* flags, test Mach-O BEFORE PE — matching the pre-existing EMITELF ladder's order. _TARGET_MACHO and _TARGET_PE come from INDEPENDENT, unguarded env vars (CYRIUS_MACHO / CYRIUS_TARGET_WIN; main.cyr has no mutual-exclusion guard), so the combined state is reachable. The old code let Mach-O win; flip the order and you silently change the conflicting-combo output (Mach-O → PE)."
detail = """
v6.0.89 (the _TARGET_* consolidation first bite: collapse the format fan-out +
entry-base ladder, duplicated in BOTH x86/fixup.cyr and aarch64/fixup.cyr, into
_emit_fmt(S)→{0=ELF,1=Mach-O-x86,2=Mach-O-ARM,3=PE} + _entry_base(S)).

An adversarial-review workflow caught a DRAFT _emit_fmt that checked `_TARGET_PE==1`
first: for `CYRIUS_MACHO=1 CYRIUS_TARGET_WIN=1` the old EMITELF (macho-first) emitted
Mach-O 8192B, the draft emitted PE 1536B — a real divergence, not a false alarm,
even though no sane build sets both. Fix: `if(_TARGET_MACHO==1)…;if(_TARGET_MACHO==2)
…;if(_TARGET_PE==1)…` so Mach-O wins, byte-identical for that combo too.

VERIFICATION SHAPE (this is the most fixup-fragile code — entry feeds every absolute
fixup): build .PREV-vs-.NEW compilers and diff EMITTED binaries across EVERY mode —
ELF-user, kernel ELF32+ELF64, shared, object, EFI (real source), AGNOS, PE, Mach-O
x86, Mach-O ARM, AND the Mach-O+PE conflict. A single-format self-host run only
exercises ELF; the macho/pe/kernel paths need the explicit matrix + ecb/ach/cass.
TEST-HARNESS TRAP that wasted a cycle: zsh does NOT word-split an unquoted `$var`, so
`env $combo sh -c …` with combo="A=1 B=1" set ONE malformed var and silently tested
the no-flags case — the output's ELF magic (not Mach-O) gave it away. Use literal
`env A=1 B=1 …`, and ALWAYS check the actual output bytes, not just the exit code.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "ts_children_list_reserve_then_fill_corrupts"
description = "TS parser children-list building: NEVER `off = TS_AST_CHILDREN_RESERVE(...)` then parse the elements into `off+i`. RESERVE does not advance the pool cursor, so each element's own sub-lists allocate at the SAME offset and stomp the parent (and vice versa) — a corrupt AST for any nested list. Use the deferred path: `base = TS_CST_TOP()`; parse each element and `TS_CST_PUSH(idx)` AFTER it's fully parsed; then `off = TS_CST_FLUSH(ts_base, base)`. The corruption was invisible for years because --parse-ts never reads lists back. v6.1.10."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["ts-frontend", "parser", "children-list", "ast", "TS_CST_PUSH", "TS_CST_FLUSH", "v6.1.10"]
content = """
**The trap**: every `src/frontend/ts/parse.cyr` list builder used
to do `off = TS_AST_CHILDREN_RESERVE(ts_base, N)` and then parse
its elements, writing each to `off + i`. But RESERVE only *peeks*
the pool cursor — it does NOT advance `used` (only COMMIT does). So
when an element is parsed, that element's own sub-lists allocate at
the SAME `used` (= off) and overwrite the parent's slots, and the
parent's later SETs overwrite the child's. Any nested list (call
args, block stmts, object props, JSX attrs/children, var bindings,
switch cases, ...) came out garbage.

**Why you won't see it in a quick check**: `cycc --parse-ts <f>`
exits 0 — but parse "success" only means no parse ERROR fired. It
never walks the retained AST, so the corruption is invisible until
something reads the lists. For years nothing did.

**The fix / the rule** (v6.1.10): deferred construction. Builders
push fully-parsed element indices onto the `_ts_cst` scratch stack
and flush one contiguous block at the end:

    var base = TS_CST_TOP();
    while (...) { var e = parse_element(); ...; TS_CST_PUSH(e); }
    var off = TS_CST_FLUSH(ts_base, base);   # contiguous, advances cursor
    if (off < 0) { return 0 - 1; }

An element is pushed only AFTER its subtree is parsed, so a run
stays contiguous on the stack even when nested builders push/flush
in between (each saves TS_CST_TOP() and flushes back to it). Two
interleaved lists at once (the template quasi/expr pair) collect
into locals + `TS_AST_CHILDREN_WRITE`. Only VALUE-walked builders
need this; type-only builders can stay on the old path (they can't
corrupt a value list once value FLUSHes advance the cursor past
them). Verify with `cycc --emit-js` (self-validates: non-zero on
any node revisited / out-of-range). Full backstory:
retros/v61x.cyml (v61x_ts_ast_allocator_corruption).
"""

[[entries]]
name = "ts_trailing_comma_generic_params_tsx"
description = "TS_PARSE_TYPE_PARAMS must accept a trailing comma before `>`: the TSX disambiguation form `const f = async <T,>(x) => x` writes `<T,>` (the comma stops the parser reading `<T>` as a JSX open tag). Pre-v6.1.10 the param loop demanded another IDENT after a comma, so every `.tsx` generic arrow failed to parse — including the consumer's real app.tsx. After consuming the comma, re-check for a `>`-family closer and stop. v6.1.10."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["ts-frontend", "parser", "tsx", "generics", "type-params", "v6.1.10"]
content = """
**The trap**: in `.tsx`, a bare `<T>(x) => x` is ambiguous with a
JSX element, so TypeScript's disambiguation is the trailing comma:
`<T,>(x) => x`. Cyrius's `TS_PARSE_TYPE_PARAMS` consumed the comma
and then unconditionally expected another type-param IDENT, so it
errored on the `>` — every generic arrow in a `.tsx` file failed
to parse, which is why the consumer's real `web/app.tsx` wouldn't
parse at all (`async <T,>(...)` twice).

**The fix** (v6.1.10): after `TS_PARSE_EXPECT(COMMA)` in the
param loop, peek for a closing token (`TS_TOK_GT` / `GT_GT` /
`GT_GT_GT` / `GT_EQ` / ...). If found, it's a trailing comma —
set done and stop instead of demanding another param. `<T>`
(no comma) already worked; this just makes `<T,>` work too.

Recognize it: a `.tsx` consumer reports "parses fine in tsc but
cyrius --parse-ts errors near a generic arrow." The bare `.ts`
equivalent (no JSX ambiguity, written `<T>`) parses, so it looks
JSX-specific — it's the trailing comma, not the JSX.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "new_pe_emitter_needs_aarch64_strict_stub"
description = "Any NEW PE syscall-reroute emitter `E*_PE` (added to backend/x86/emit.cyr) must also get a `fn E*_PE(S) { return 0; }` stub in backend/aarch64/emit.cyr. parse_expr.cyr references the emitter unconditionally inside its statically-dead `if (_TARGET_PE == 1)` block, so cycc's symbol resolution needs the symbol to exist when the aarch64 backend builds — a missing stub fires `warning: undefined function 'E*_PE'`, which is FATAL under `--strict`. v6.1.17."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["pe", "aarch64", "stub", "symbol-resolution", "strict", "syscall-reroute", "v6.1.17"]
content = """
**The trap**: v6.1.17 added `ENANOSLEEP_PE` to `backend/x86/emit.cyr`
(routes `nanosleep(35)` → `kernel32!Sleep`) and wired it into
`parse_expr.cyr`'s `_TARGET_PE == 1` block — both the literal
`sc_num == 35` case and the `EPE_SYSCALL_DYNAMIC` argc==3 candidate.
The x86 build + local self-host + cass all passed. But the
**aarch64** cross-build fired `warning: undefined function
'ENANOSLEEP_PE'` (twice). It only *warns* (non-fatal) on a plain
build — so a forgotten stub sails through unless you build `--strict`
(CI / `cyrius build --strict`), where it's a hard error.

**Why**: `parse_expr.cyr` calls every `E*_PE` emitter unconditionally
inside `if (_TARGET_PE == 1)`. On aarch64 `_TARGET_PE` is always 0 so
the branch is statically dead at runtime, but cycc resolves symbols
before that's known, so the fn must exist. `backend/aarch64/emit.cyr`
therefore carries a `return 0` stub for the ENTIRE PE cohort
(EWRITE_PE, EGETTICKS_PE, ECREATEDIR_PE, EPE_SYSCALL_DYNAMIC, …). A
new emitter is the one piece you forget.

**The fix**: add `fn ENANOSLEEP_PE(S): i64 { return 0; }` to the
aarch64 cohort. (The `cx` backend does NOT stub these — it already
emits the undefined-fn warning for the whole cohort and builds anyway,
because it isn't a `--strict` target; matching that means you leave cx
alone, you don't stub only your one new fn there.)

Recognize it: a new `E*_PE` lands, x86 + Windows are green, then a
`--strict` aarch64/macOS build (or CI) breaks on "undefined function."
Grep `backend/aarch64/emit.cyr` for the existing `_PE) { return 0; }`
cohort and add yours next to `EPE_SYSCALL_DYNAMIC`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "per_fn_local_tables_indexed_by_slot_not_var"
description = "The four per-fn local tables (fn_local_names / fn_local_depths / fn_local_types / fn_local_slice) are indexed by SFLC, which counts stack-frame SLOTS, NOT vars — a `stack var buf[N]` registers N/8 filler slots — so any frame larger than ~2 KB silently overran the old 256/576-entry tables (CVE-24). v6.1.40 relocated all four to the heap top at 16384 slots each + added a loud SFLC cap."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["compiler", "local-tables", "sflc", "heap-cap", "overflow", "cve-24", "v6.1.40"]
content = """
**The trap (CVE-24)**: cyrius's four per-function local tables —
`fn_local_names`, `fn_local_depths`, `fn_local_types`,
`fn_local_slice` — are indexed by `SFLC` (the stack-frame local
count). `SFLC` counts stack-frame **SLOTS**, not user-visible
variables. A `stack var buf[N]` (a byte array on the frame) doesn't
register as one entry — it registers **N/8 filler slots** (one per
8-byte slot the array occupies). So a single `stack var buf[2048]`
burns 256 table entries by itself.

The old tables were sized 256 / 576 entries. Any function whose
frame exceeded ~2 KB of slot-arrays silently ran `SFLC` past the
table end and wrote past the region — a heap overrun with no
diagnostic. Self-host never tripped it (cycc's own fns stay small),
so it was invisible until a consumer with a large stack buffer (the
daimon report) hit it.

**The fix (v6.1.40)**: relocate all four tables to the heap top,
each sized **16384 slots**:

  - fn_local_names   @ 0x5D9D000
  - fn_local_depths  @ 0x5DBD000
  - fn_local_types   @ 0x5DDD000
  - fn_local_slice   @ 0x5DFD000

plus a LOUD `SFLC` cap check (error + exit, not silent truncation)
so a future overrun reports the slot count and the file to raise,
instead of corrupting the heap.

**The footgun behind the report — local vs global array sizing**:
the array-size convention differs by scope, which is exactly what
let the frame grow past expectation:

  - **local** `var a[N]` = **N BYTES**, rounded UP to 8 (so
    `var a[5]` still consumes one 8-byte slot; `var a[2048]`
    consumes 256 slots).
  - **global** `var a[N]` = **N i64 SLOTS** (N*8 bytes).

So a buffer that looks identical in source (`var a[2048]`) is 2 KB
on the stack but 16 KB in `.bss` as a global. Size local arrays by
BYTE count; size globals by slot count. Mixing the two mental
models is how the daimon frame quietly grew past the old cap.

**Recognize again**: any "large stack buffer corrupts compiler
state / heap" shape, or a consumer whose fn has a multi-KB
`stack var buf[N]`. Check `SFLC` against the table cap; the slot
count is `frame_bytes / 8`, not the var count. Related:
`large_fn_local_var_array_is_bss_not_stack` (the dual — big
fn-local arrays land in `.bss`, not the stack frame).
"""

[[entries]]
name = "phase0_growable_grow_path_self_host_invisible"
description = "The v6.2.0 growable pressure tables (fixup_tbl, fn-tables, codebuf) never grow during cycc's own self-compile — cycc is at 6486/8192 fns and ~1 MB of a 3 MB codebuf, so the realloc / rehash / relocation code is dead on the self-host path AND on every check.sh test. A bug in the grow/rehash logic is therefore invisible to byte-identical self-host. The ONLY thing that catches it is a forced-grow test: shrink the initial cap, self-compile, and cmp against the no-grow reference."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["growable", "self-host-invisible", "fn-tables", "codebuf", "fixup", "testing", "v6.2.0"]
content = """
**The trap**: Phase 0 (v6.2.0) made three fixed tables growable —
`fixup_tbl` (`_fixup_grow`), the 16 fn-tables + 2 hashes
(`_fnt_grow`, with a name-hash rehash), and `codebuf`
(`_codebuf_grow`, off-heap relocate). All three GROW paths are
**cold on every path the test suite walks**: cycc self-compiles
with ~6486 functions (the cap starts at 8192) and ~1 MB of
generated code (the codebuf cap starts at 3 MB), so neither
`_fnt_grow` nor `_codebuf_grow` ever fires. A subtle bug — a wrong
copy length, a stale base pointer after relocation, a botched
rehash — produces a **byte-identical self-host and a green
check.sh** while silently corrupting any real consumer that does
cross the cap.

**The only test that exercises it**: artificially shrink the
initial cap so a NORMAL self-compile is forced through many
grows, then prove the output is unchanged:

  # fn-tables: set `_fnt_cap = 64` / `_fnt_hash_mask = 63` in the driver,
  # build cycc_small, then:
  cat src/main.cyr | ./cycc_small > out      # forces ~7 grows + rehashes
  cat src/main.cyr | ./build/cycc > ref      # no-grow reference (cap 8192)
  cmp out ref                                # MUST be identical

  # codebuf: `_codebuf_cap = 8192` → ~7 relocations; same cmp.

Run the forced-grow test on **both** x86 AND aarch64 — the
aarch64 start-hash build + `live[]` bitmap are mirrored code; the
x86 forced-grow does not cover them. The aarch64 variant: shrink
the cap in `main_aarch64.cyr` and run `cross-os-selfhost.sh pi`
(it self-hosts on real ARM, which forces the grow there).

**Recognize again**: ANY migration of a fixed cap/table to
growable, where the compiler's own usage stays under the cap.
"Self-host is byte-identical" proves the RELOCATION-equivalent
(no-grow) path; it says nothing about the grow path. Mandatory
forced-grow + differential-corpus before trusting it. Sibling
trap: `phase0_growable_relocation_and_scattered_cap`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "phase0_growable_relocation_and_scattered_cap"
description = "Two mechanics that bite when migrating cycc's fixed tables to growable: (1) a relocating buffer (codebuf) is only safe if every access re-derives from the base gvar and never holds a captured pointer across an EB — and the disp32 patch sites do an 8-byte read-modify-write that bypasses EB's cap-check, so the grow needs a guard band; (2) the 8192 fn-cap was a magic literal scattered across 6 subsystems and textually colliding with 5 UNRELATED 8192-capped tables, so the swap had to be surgical per-context, never a global replace."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["growable", "codebuf", "fn-tables", "relocation", "magic-number", "v6.2.0"]
content = """
**Relocation safety (codebuf)**: `_codebuf_grow` `alloc()`s a new
buffer and repoints `_codebuf_base`. That is only correct because
EVERY codebuf access re-derives `_codebuf_base + offset` fresh:
- the disp32 patch sites (`var a = _codebuf_base + GCP(S); S64(a, …)`)
  capture-and-store with NO `EB` in between, so no grow can run
  between the capture and the use;
- the DSE/LASE/regalloc peephole passes read+patch already-emitted
  code AFTER all emit, when the buffer is stable.
A pattern that captured `_codebuf_base + cp` and then called `EB`
(which can grow → relocate) before using it would dereference the
freed old buffer. There is none today — keep it that way.

The disp32 stores also do an 8-byte read-modify-write at `cp`
(`S64(a, (L64(a) >> 32 << 32) | disp)`), writing 4 bytes PAST the
4-byte slot, and they bypass `EB`'s cap-check entirely. So
`_codebuf_grow` triggers at `cp >= _codebuf_cap - 64` (a 64-byte
guard band), not at the exact cap, or the last RMW before a grow
would write past the buffer end. The cx bytecode backend has its
OWN codebuf at `0x54A000` (separate region, still fixed 512 KB) —
it is NOT `_codebuf_base`.

**The scattered magic number (fn-tables)**: `8192` (the fn-cap)
was hard-coded in ~6 independent places — `REGFN`'s cap-check,
the `fn_name_hash` + `fn_start_hash` probe/mask/clear bounds, the
`live[1024]` DCE bitmap, and the 85 %-full warning — with NO single
source of truth. Worse, the literal `8192` also appears in 5
UNRELATED capped tables (var table, IR pool, PE reloc, struct
field pool, the TS scratch stack). A blind `8192 → _fnt_cap` would
have corrupted those. The migration was surgical per-context:
`& 8191 → & _fnt_hash_mask` (hash masks only), `probes/sh_clr <
8192 → _fnt_cap` (hash bounds only), `live[1024] → live[4096]`
(the DCE bitmap, sized to the 32768 ceiling), REGFN's check → the
grow call. Everything now reads one `_fnt_cap`.

**Recognize again**: any "raise/remove a fixed cap" task where the
cap value is a bare literal. Grep first; a literal that doubles as
an unrelated table's size will silently break that table.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "agnos_target_stub_predicated_on_obsolete_kernel_surface"
description = "A `#ifdef CYRIUS_TARGET_AGNOS return 0;` stub written against an EARLIER kernel ABI silently rots once the kernel grows the missing syscall — the stub keeps 'working' (returns a deterministic 0) so nothing fails loud, while every consumer re-rolls a direct-syscall workaround. Re-check the live kernel ABI before trusting a frozen-surface comment."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["agnos", "stub", "syscall", "chrono", "stale", "v6.2.6"]
content = """
**The trap**: `lib/chrono.cyr`'s AGNOS branches for monotonic time
(`clock_now_ns()`) and `sleep_ms()` were fixed-`return 0` / no-op
stubs, with a comment justifying them — "agnos has no monotonic /
sleep syscall in the frozen 0-33 surface (228=clock_gettime,
35=nanosleep are out of range)." True when WRITTEN (v6.0.56). But
the agnos kernel grew `uptime_ms`#40 + `sleep_ms`#41 at 1.43.x (the
cyrius-doom frame clock / pacing primitives). The stubs never
faulted — `clock_now_ms()` just always returned 0 and `sleep_ms()`
busy-spun — so no gate, no smoke, no self-host caught it. It
surfaced only when the v6.2.5 `dig`/`yo` net-tool ports needed real
timing and had to call `syscall(40)`/`syscall(41)` DIRECTLY,
bypassing chrono. Classic "found by ports": the placebo that returns
a plausible value is more dangerous than one that crashes.

**The fix** (v6.2.6): add `sys_uptime_ms`#40 / `sys_sleep_ms`#41
wrappers (new `SysNrAgnosTimer` enum) to
`lib/syscalls_x86_64_agnos.cyr`; point chrono's agnos branches at
them (`clock_now_ns()` = `sys_uptime_ms()*1e6`; `sleep_ms()` agnos
branch calls `sys_sleep_ms(ms)`, guard `ms<=0`). Wall-clock#46 was
already correctly bound at v6.2.3 — this was the monotonic+sleep
counterpart it didn't cover. Extended `agnos-crossbuild-gate.sh`
with a chrono monotonic/sleep probe so a re-stub is now caught.

**Recognize again**: any `#ifdef CYRIUS_TARGET_AGNOS return 0;`
(or no-op) guarded by a comment naming a kernel version / "frozen
0-N surface." That comment is a timestamp, not an invariant — the
kernel ABI doc (`agnos/docs/development/agnos-userland-abi.md`) is
canonical and grows. Grep the doc for the capability before
trusting the stub; a stub that returns a deterministic 0 will not
fail loud when the assumption expires.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "agnos_server_socket_accept_commits_v6222"
description = "AGNOS gained inbound TCP at kernel 1.45.5/.6 (sock_listen#56 / sock_accept#57); cyrius v6.2.22 wires lib/net.cyr's sock_bind/listen/accept via a listen<->fd adapter. The non-obvious trap: sock_accept(#57) COMMITS the accept kernel-side (the conn is ESTABLISHED + marked accepted, never re-handed-out), so if the LOCAL 8-slot fd table is full you MUST reap the returned conn_id (#50) or it leaks a kernel slot forever. Also: a consumer's 'undefined CLONE_VM on --agnos' is almost always STALE vendored thread.cyr, not a lib bug."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["agnos", "sockets", "net.cyr", "syscall", "v6.2.22", "thread.cyr", "stale-vendored"]
content = """
**AGNOS server sockets (v6.2.22).** The kernel exposes inbound TCP as two
1-arg syscalls: `sock_listen(port)#56` (merges bind+listen -> a listen_id
0..7) and `sock_accept(listen_id)#57` (non-blocking -> next ESTABLISHED
conn_id 0..7, or -1 = WOULD_BLOCK). `lib/net.cyr`'s `sock_bind`/`sock_listen`/
`sock_accept` route onto these on `--agnos` via a **listen<->fd adapter** in
`lib/syscalls_x86_64_agnos.cyr` (parallel to the v6.2.3 conn<->fd adapter):
bind stashes the port, listen issues #56, accept issues #57 + wraps the
conn_id in a fresh tagged fd riding the existing #48/#49/#50 path. Both are
1-arg, so NO codegen change.

**Trap 1 — #57 COMMITS the accept.** Unlike a peek, `tcp_accept` sets the
kernel conn's accepted-bit and never re-hands it out (and `tcp_close` on the
listener skips accepted children). So in `sock_accept`, after #57 returns a
conn_id, if your local fd allocation fails (the cyrius 8-slot table is full:
1 listen + 7 conns), you MUST `sys_sock_close(cid)` (#50) BEFORE returning the
error — otherwise that kernel conn slot leaks forever and, over the server's
life, the kernel's 8-slot table is exhausted. (The client #47 path has no such
window — the fd is allocated BEFORE the kernel call.) Caught by adversarial
review, not the compile-only gate.

**Trap 2 — clear ALL slot tables on close.** A bind-without-listen (or bind
then a FAILED listen) close must zero `listen_port` too, or a recycled fd-slot
inherits a stale port and silently mis-listens. `sys_close` clears conn_tbl +
listen_tbl + listen_port uniformly on every socket-fd close.

**Trap 3 — 'undefined CLONE_VM on --agnos' is NOT a lib bug.** `lib/thread.cyr`
self-guards agnos since v6.2.3 (`#ifdef CYRIUS_TARGET_AGNOS` -> thread_agnos.cyr
no-op mutexes; the `mmap.cyr`/CLONE_VM body is `#ifndef`-gated). A stdlib
consumer hitting `undefined variable 'CLONE_VM'` on `--agnos` is almost always
running a STALE vendored `thread.cyr` (pre-v6.2.3) — the fix is `cyrius deps`
to refresh, NOT a compiler/lib change. (This is why sankoch 2.4.4's lock no-op
is self-sufficiency, not a crash fix — CHANGELOG 6.2.22.)
"""
